<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Water Supplies Will Remain Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun,
speaking at a conference marking Guangdong province's
thirty-second year of providing water for Hong Kong today, urged
the Guangdong provincial government to work harder to improve
water supplies for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Jiang called on water officials to improve management,
guarantee water quality and offer better services to Hong Kong's
six million people.
</P>
<P>
According to Hu Man Shiu, director of Hong Kong's Water
Supplies Department, Hong Kong suffered from a drought from the
autumn of 1962 to the summer of 1963 that caused severe water
shortages in Hong Kong, which has no major lakes, rivers or
underground water supply.
</P>
<P>
At that time, China came to the rescue with a water-supply
project, bringing water from Dongguan City in Guangdong Province
for a distance of 83 km to the Shenzhen River, which reaches Hong
Kong, he explained.
</P>
<P>
The project was renovated three times and provides more than
700 million cubic meters of water to Hong Kong a year, meeting
over 70 percent of Hong Kong's water needs, he said.
</P>
<P>
He reminded the more than 600 people in the audience that
Guangdong's water supply has provided Hong Kong with the
fundamental means to embark on a road to riches.
</P>
<P>
Not a few people attribute Hong Kong's success to low taxes,
free and fair market competition, a sound legal and financial
structure, a sophisticated infrastructure, a capable working
population and a group of aggressive entrepreneurs, he said.
</P>
<P>
But, he stressed, the most important and a relatively
inconspicuous reason is the stable and reliable water
supply. Otherwise, Hong Kong's development history could have been
rewritten.
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
