<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Junta Not to Give Up Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, June 10 (Xinhua) - The military junta in Sierra
Leone said it never asked the deposed civilian government for
money and cars in return of returining power to civilians.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to a claim made on the BBC African network programme
on Tuesday that the junta was willing to give up power, a
military spokesman said, "no transaction like that happened".
</P>
<P>
"We are still going for negotiated settlement which would
auger peace for Sierra Leone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said a negotiated settlement would involve all
political parties, the rebel and other interested parties.
</P>
<P>
According to a report published by the International Committee
of the Red Cross (ICRC) on Tuesday, 120 civilians died as a
result of Nigerian-led bombardment by ECOMOG troops.
</P>
<P>
It said about 200 civilians were wounded.
</P>
<P>
Civilian exodus was put at 25,000, mainly evacuated to parts
of the north while 20,000 people crossed the border into Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The capital remained calm but there has been a considerable
escalation of prices on essential consumer goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
