<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Dismisses Change of EU Stability Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
today ruled out the possibility to make any change of the
stability pact for the planned single European currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
"I have made it clear that there will be no renegotiation of
the stability pact," Waigel said in Berlin in an apparent response
to French plans announced Monday to delay the pact.
</P>
<P>
French Finance Minister Dominique Strausse-Kahn Monday said
Paris needed time to consider whether to sign the pact, which
would impose huge forfeit on countries for failing to limit budget
deficits within 3 percent of the Gross Domestic Product as
required for qualifying for euro membership.
</P>
<P>
Waigel strongly backed the pact which was reached after tough
negotiations by European Union (EU) leaders last December and was
supposed to be signed at the EU Amsterdam summit slated for June
16-17.
</P>
<P>
German industry today urged the German government to reject the
French move.
</P>
<P>
"The stability pact must remain -- the German government must
be tough on this, " said Dieter Rath, spokesman for the
influential Confederation of German Industry.
</P>
<P>
French Deputy Minsiter for European Affairs Pierre Moscovici,
said in Paris that France would not give in to any pressure and
the pact could not be approved at Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
In addition, German main opposition Social Democrats (SPD)
today announced that it would decline a revised EU Maastricht II
treaty if it failed to carry provisions on job creation.
</P>
<P>
Bonn opposes an EU job program, which Rath said "would not
create a single new job."
</P>
<P>
The revised EU treaty is expected to pass the Amsterdam summit.
</P>
<P>
SPD, controlling the upper house of the German parliament, can
block the EU Maastricht II accord, which needs the approval of at
least two thirds of the votes at both lower and upper chambers of
the parliament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
