<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Computer Expert Hopeful About Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Software production could become a
major earner for Zambia if fully exploited, a Zambian computer
expert has said.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted Dove computing director Jeremiah
Phiri as saying in Kitwe, northern Zambia, at the weekend that
the computer software production is a potential money spinner
because it requires very little material inputs.
</P>
<P>
"All you need is a computer and diskettes and a brain, then
you can produce your software," Phiri said.
</P>
<P>
He said the market is readily available in the country as 60
percent of companies are using computers.
</P>
<P>
At present there are very few local companies that produce
software and most firms only sold computers, he said.
</P>
<P>
People face problems because they prefer to import software,
some of which is of inferior quality, said the computer expert.
</P>
<P>
"Because the software is from developed countries, people
think it is always of high quality. Some of the software packages
have been rejected in developed countries and are just dumped in
Africa where people accept anything," Phiri said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
