<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Seek War Reparations From Iraq's Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran said today that it will seek
reparations from Iraq's oil sale for accommodating war refugees
and for pollution in Iran's territorial waters in the Persian Gulf
in the aftermath of Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Hosseini, director-general in charge of foreign
nationals' affairs of the Interior Ministry, was quoted by the
state-run Tehran Radio as saying that "Commission on Estimation of
Reparation located in Geneva, Switzerland, ruled in its latest
session that the cost incurred by Iran would have to be paid from
revenues earned from Iraq's oil sale."
</P>
<P>
Hosseini said that Iran will submit the required documentation
of its financial damage to the U.N. commission.
</P>
<P>
Iran was entitled to the reparations in view of influx of some
1.2 million Kurdish refugees as the result of the Iraqi invasion
of Kuwait in 1990, the Iranian official said.
</P>
<P>
However, the report gave no detail on how much reparations Iran
seeks.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and the U.N. signed last year the "oil-for-food" deal,
which allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over
six months. Some 30 percent of the amount is earmarked for war
compensation and U.N. operations in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
