<HEADLINE> Iran Understands Turkey's Security Concern: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Iranian official
said here today that Iran understood Turkey's concern over its
border security and would cooperate with Turkey in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at the Iranian Embassy here,
visiting Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Alaeddin Brujerdi said
that he had exchanged views with Turkish officials on recent
developments in the region and the security issues as well.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran attached great importance to the security
problem on the two countries' border area, adding that the
Iranian government would extend efforts to help Turkey ensure
its border security.
</P>
<P>
In response to Turkey's appeal for preventing the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) rebels from sheltering in Iran,
Brujerdi said that the Iranian government had ordered its
security forces to arrest those rebels if they tried to
enter Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian deputy foreign minister also denied reports that
there were terrorists' camps on the Iranian territory.
</P>
<P>
Brujerdi arrived here Monday on a surprise visit to Turkey to
voice Iran's concern over Turkey's large-scale military operation
in northern Iraq to wipe out PKK rebels.
</P>
<P>
He carried a message from Iranian President Ali Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani to his Turkish counterpart Suleyman Demirel, but the
content of the letter was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
However, the Iranian official said that all countries should
respect the independence and territorial integrity of Iraq,
indicating that Turkey should put an end to its cross-border
military operation in northern Iraq as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the Turkish government to take effective
measures against the activities of the alleged anti-Iranian
groups on the Turkish territory.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Iran and Turkey should promote their relations,
Brujerdi said that the scheduled participation of Iranian
President Rafsanjani in the upcoming M-8 Group summit was a good
evidence of Iran's good will to develop its cooperation with
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000 Turkish government troops have launched a
massive cross-border military operation in pursuit of the
outlawed PKK rebels in northern Iraq, drawing severe criticism
from many regional countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
