<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Check Up On Extravagant Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese authorities will send
special insection teams to some provinces, autonomous regions,
municipalities, as well as central government departments to
supervise their work, aiming to put an end to extravagant spending.
</P>
<P>
The teams, organized by the Central Commission for Discipline
Inspection of the Communist Party of China and the Ministry of
Supervision, will check up on how these localities and departments
are being managed with regards to using public funds.
</P>
<P>
The localities and departments are required to take steps to
control excessive spending on office buildings, meetings and
celebration ceremonies, the installment of too many telephones or
the purchase of mobile phones with public funds.
</P>
<P>
Use of public money for overindulgent "business dinners,"
buying luxury cars, and travelling overseas in the name of
research will be also reviewed by the teams.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting held for the inspectors, Hou Zongbin, deputy
secretary of the CPC Central Commission for Discipline Inspection,
said it is key to the anti-corruption campaign this year to study
Jiang Zemin's speech on the anti-corruption campaign and to
implement the regulations of the CPC Central Committee and the
State Council in this regard.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
