<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share-Holding System for Shanghai Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's Hongqiao Airport, one
of the three largest in China, will introduce a joint-stock system
to raise funds for further development and improving efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The airport will set up the Hongqiao International Airport
Joint-Stock Company Ltd. this month. Shareholders will mainly be
large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Authorities say that the majority of funds raised will be used
to purchase part of the management rights of Pudong International
Airport, and a small amount will be kept for purpose of developing
Hongqiao Airport.
</P>
<P>
Pudong International Airport will go into operation by the end
of 1999. The Shanghai Airport Joint-Stock (Group) Company, which
will soon be formed, will be entitled by the Shanghai Municipal
State-Owned Assets Management Committee to manage state-owned
assets of the two airports.
</P>
<P>
The civil aviation industry of Shanghai has grown rapidly over
the past few years. Hongqiao Airport handled 12.3 million
passengers last year, a 11.5 percent rise over 1995, while its
designed capacity is only for 9.6 million passengers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the airport's number of take-offs and
landings of airplanes, the passenger handling capacity, and the
cargo and mail handling capacity increased by 18.4, 22.6, and 23.2
percent annually, respectively, during the 1991-1995 period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
