<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cooperates With UNDP to Strengthen Coastal Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- In a move to strengthen
environmental protection and preserve coastal resources, China
today launched a project for integrated coastal management in the
northern part of the South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
With 1.1 million US dollars in funding from the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), the project will establish a
coordinated management system among the provincial governments of
Guangdong, Guangxi, and Hainan provinces to improve monitoring and
supervision of the environment.
</P>
<P>
After the completion of the project in three years, an
experimental zone will be set up in each of the three provinces,
focusing on the sustainable development of fishery resources, port
management, and multi-layered development of oceanic resources.
</P>
<P>
The rapid economic growth of China's coastal areas has led to
the deterioration of its coastal environment and resources, which
has drawn increasing attention from the central government.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have been made to tighten supervision over the coastal
areas. For example, China has set up a large oceanic environmental
monitoring system which has conducted in-depth studies into the
coastal ecological systems, and a second survey of the nation's
polluted ocean areas will start soon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several oceanic environmental protection zones have
been set up, and a series of laws and regulations on oceanic
environmental protection have been drawn up.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
