<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clash Recovered Between Nigerian and Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, June 11 (Xinhua) - All is now quiet at the Lungi
international airport in Sierra Leone after Nigerian and Sierra
Leone soldiers traded mogtar shells on Tuesday night, local
residents said.
</P>
<P>
There has been no report of casualities, but state radio
quoting an announcement from the military junta, attributed the
clash to a "small misunderstanding between a skeleton of the
Nigerian army and a unit of the Sierra Leone army''.
</P>
<P>
The airport is located 12 miles from the capital across the
Sierra Leone river and can be reached from the mainland by ferry.
Residents near the airport reached by telephone said the gunfire
lasted between 10 and 15 minutes and was reechoed in the city
itself.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone thought it was the imminent military invasion by
Nigerian-led ECOMOG forces and we dived under our beds," one
Lungi resident said.
</P>
<P>
"The situation was quickly arrested and is now under perfect
control," the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said the clash highlights the state of tension
at the airport with Nigerian and Sierra Leone soldiers facing
each other with itchy fingers on the trigger. No commercial
flights have arriveed since the junta lifted the air, land and
sea blockade it imposed after the coup.
</P>
<P>
"We are virtually idle except for the infrequent arrival of
ECOMOG helicopters from Monrovia and the take-off and landing of
helicopters belonging to the Sierra Leone army. Each side watches
the other's aircraft but does not interfere", a civil aviation
worker told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the junta has denied it asked for 43, 000,000
dollars from the ousted civilian government in return to give
back power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
