<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Enhances Security for Liberia's Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping force
in Liberia, known as ECOMOG, has appointed electoral officers to
coordinate security at the grassroot level of the country during
the elections billed for mid-July.
</P>
<P>
The step was to strengthen the ECOMOG security network for the
election and further boost the confidence and sense of security
of the Liberian populace, especially in the hinterland, the force
commander major-general Victor Malu said on Tuesday in Monrovia,
capital of Liberia.
</P>
<P>
According to Malu, the ECOMOG electoral officers will continue
to receive regular briefings so that they can effectively police
the areas assigned to them.
</P>
<P>
Commending the Liberian politicians who have started to expand
their activities into the hinterland, Malu said they should go
into remote towns and villages instead of towns near Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG chief also reiterated the force's readiness to
provide additional security to encourage politicians entering the
hinterland. ECOMOG has promised to escort politicians to such
places for election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
According to Malu, the military coup in neighboring Sierra
Leone is now generating a new wave of refugees who are fleeing
into Liberia to escape the anarchy and insecurity in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG troops stationed in some of the border areas with
Sierra Leone have been giving regular reports of the rattled
Sierra Leoneans escaping brutalities by the rebels and coupists,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
