<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing to resettle 337,200 People in five years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- China's fourth and newest
municipality of Chongqing is scheduled to move 337,200 people out
of the Three Gorges Area within five years, or 67,400 people per
year.
</P>
<P>
The figure still only accounts for about one-third of the total
of 1.2 million people to be evacuated from the Three Gorges
area. The resettlement will be completed by the year 2009.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, which gained municipality status in March, is
responsible for the resettlement of about one million people.
</P>
<P>
The water level of the Three Gorges, where the world's largest
hydro-electric power project is being built, will rise sharply
after the river is dammed this November, and many places around
the area will be flooded.
</P>
<P>
"The resettlement of people in the Three Gorges areas is a key
factor for the ultimate success of the project," said Gan Yuping,
vice-mayor of the city, who is in charge of the resettlement.
</P>
<P>
"So we must make sure that people in the area will be moved out
in time and be resettled comfortably," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled resettlement of people in the Three Gorges area
began in 1993. By the end of 1996, 3.4 billion yuan (about 410
million US dollars) had been spent on the relocation of 28,000
rural residents in Chongqing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
