<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Nearly Doubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus
jumped 92.7 percent in April, to 1,091.8 billion yen (9.8 billion
dollars) compared with its level a year earlier, the Japanese
Finance Ministry announced today.
</P>
<P>
Exports in April advanced 21.6 percent to 4,313.4 billion yen
(38.9 billion dollars), up for the 21st consecutive month.
Imports grew 9.3 percent to 3,209.8 billion yen (29.6 billion
dollars), rising for the 33rd month in a row, the ministry said in
a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
In particular, automobile exports increased 32.2 percent in
value and 20.2 percent in volume from a year earlier as auto
manufacturers, faced with the declining domestic demand resulting
from the consumption tax hike on April 1, turned their eyes to
foreign markets, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus of goods and services in April amounted to
417.6 billion yen (3.8 billion dollars), compared with a deficit
of 32.5 billion yen (300 million dollars) a year before. Surplus
in merchandise trade soared and a deficit in services trade,
including tourism, expanded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
