<HEADLINE> S. Africa Black Graduates Difficult to Get Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's well-educated
black youngsters are battling to find jobs as companies in the
country are opting for experience rather than educational
qualifications.
</P>
<P>
The number of black graduates from universities and technical
schools is soaring in recent years, but this does not mean black
graduates have easy access to good work, personnel agencies and
educationists said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A study found that from 1991 to 1994 the number of degrees,
diplomas, and certificates awarded by universities to Africans
grew by 42 percent against a comparable figure for whites of one
percent.
</P>
<P>
At technical schools, the figure for Africans rose by 167
percent against 10 percent for whites.
</P>
<P>
Last year there were still nearly twice as many whites with
degrees, 403,000, as there were African, of whom 188,000 had
degrees. Coloreds had 24,000 and Indians 35,000.
</P>
<P>
However, the increase in the levels of education of blacks has
far outstripped the jobs availble, educationists complained. They
urged companies to put training programs in place to help
graduates make the transition from the academic world to the
workplace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
