<HEADLINE> Dollar Continues Falling in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States dollar slipped to
the 110 yen range on the Tokyo Foreign Exchange today as a massive
amount of selling resulted from concerns over the resurgence of
Japan's huge trade surplus.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency briefly dropped to its lowest mark for the
year at 110.68 yen shortly before 5 p.m..
</P>
<P>
At 5 p.m., the dollar was trading at 110.89-92 yen, down from
112.30-33 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo, and 112.35-45 yen late Tuesday
in New York.
</P>
<P>
On the stock exchange, share prices dropped sharply due to
losses stemming from blue-chip exporters following the
U.S. dollar's descent to the 110 yen level at one point.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
of the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed at 20,289.93, down 242.62
points or 1.8 percent from Tuesday's end.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all issues on the
First Section, fell 5.16 points or 0.34 percent to 1,508.83.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section expanded to an estimated 380
million shares from the previous day's 330.80 million shares.
</P>
