<HEADLINE> Kenyan-Indian Trade Shoots up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Kenya and India has
increased by almost 20 percent in the past few years with India
in favorable, the Kenya Times newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Indian High Commissioner T.P. Sreenivasan said on Tuesday that
although Kenyan exports to India have risen tremendously over the
same period, the imbalance of trade is in favor of India.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government is ready to work with its Kenyan
counterpart in narrowing the deficit, he said when paying a
courtesy call on Kenyan Health Minister Jackson Mulinge.
</P>
<P>
India is planning to send a team of doctors to Kenya's
Kenyatta National Hospital to assist in grading facilities and
research work in the area of heart treatment, he revealed, adding
that Indian drug manufacturing companies are also ready to set up
units in kenya.
</P>
<P>
"The government of India is willing to cooperate with Kenya in
various fields including the health sector and especially in the
area of pharmaceuticals," he said, lamenting India's low share in
the local pharmaceutical market.
</P>
<P>
Mulinge praised the relations between the two countries,
urging India to provide training opportunities to Kenyan health
personnel.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that India send technicians to Kenya to train
local personnel or sponsor the ministry's staff for short-term
courses in India.
</P>
<P>
Most drugs in use locally in the eastern African country are
imported from India, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
