<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Macao Ready to Celebrate HK's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Macao will be lit up and immersed
with dance and singing on the night of June 30 to mark China's
resumption of its exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
That is part of the activities prepared by more than 30 local
societies and organizations in Macao, which will also return to
China in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Celebrations in Macao will last for about a month starting from
 mid-June, Xinhua has learned.
</P>
<P>
The Macao Basic Law Promotion Association, women's
organizations, returned Chinese bodies, businessmen's
associations, grassroots organs like neighborhood associations,
and bodies of vendors, fishermen, vegetable farmers, and
organizations of students, teachers, Guangdong Opera troupes,
sports, arts and the media will all hold celebrations at the
historical moment.
</P>
<P>
The film-show of "The Opium War" on coming Thursday will kick
off the series of activities, followed by symposia, grand evening
parties, performances, photo contests and exhibitions, martial
arts display, football matches, tree-planting, lectures on Hong
Kong's history and a countdown to handover, among others.
</P>
<P>
The peak time of the celebrations will be around July
1. Streets and many office buildings in Macao will be lit up at
night and decorated with colorful flags during June 30 and July
1, according to arrangements by the Macao Compatriots Preparatory
 Committee for the Celebration of Hong Kong's Return to the
Motherland, which coordinates all celebrations in Macao.
</P>
<P>
A grand gala will be held at a square in central Macao from 8
p.m. on June 30 to 00:30 a.m. on July 1. The most exciting moment
will come when thousands of people shout out a countdown at
midnight, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Another dance party will follow on the night of July 1, when
one more evening party organized by the preparatory committee will
 stage on. Dancers and singers from Beijing and Macao will put on
a three-night celebration performance in Macao.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch will host a
reception party on July 1 to mark Hong Kong's return. Wang Qiren,
director of the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch, and Macao
Governor Vasco Rocha Vieira, are expected to deliver speeches at a
 reception to be attended by more than 600 people.
</P>
<P>
Macao media have evidently increased coverage of events in
Hong Kong over the past weeks. Some Chinese newspapers have
applied to send reporters to Hong Kong for the handover
coverage. The local television station is expected to show the
ceremony live. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singer Donates 1.7 Million Yuan to Charity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A young folk singer from south
China's Guangdong Province has donated in Beijing the 1.7 million
yuan she collected from her individual concerts and some related
activities to a charity for the disabled and some cultural
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Liang Yurong, who sings ballads in the Guangdong dialect, gave
one million yuan to the China Disabled Persons' Federation and the
remainder to the China Federation of Literary and Art Circles, the
China Quyi (folk art forms) Artists' Federation, and three folk
art schools in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
A winner of both provincial and national awards for artists,
Liang has been invited to perform in Singapore, Hong Kong and
Macao. She has become popular in these places, where many of the
residents speak the Guangdong dialect.
</P>
<P>
Liang will give a concert at the Chang'an Theater in Beijing on
June 13. She will be joined by well-known Hong Kong pop stars
including Elizabeth Wang Ming-Chun.
</P>
<P>
Last April, Liang also gave two charity performances in
Guangzhou and Foshan in Guangdong province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
