<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Inflation Rate Down in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- China's retail price index
increased by 0.8 percentage points last month from the same month
of 1996, according to a government report.
</P>
<P>
The index went down by 1.1 percent from last April, according
to the report jointly released today by the State Planning
Commission and State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Among all provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions, the
two biggest decreases in retail prices emerged in Shanghai and
Guangdong Province last month, standing at 1.6 and 1.1 percentage
points, respectively, lower than in the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Beijing and Sichuan Province registered a
year-on-year increase of 4.3 and 3.7 percentage points,
respectively, in the retail price index, which represented the two
highest inflation rates in the country.
</P>
<P>
During the January-May period, the year-on-year increase margin
for retail prices stood at 0.1 and 0.2 percentage point in
Shanghai and Guangdong, representing the smallest price rise in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The biggest increase margin appeared in Beijing and Sichuan
during the first five months this year, at 5.1 percentage points
higher than the corresponding period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the January-May period, the retail price index of 36 Chinese
major cities went up by an average of 1.9 points from the same
period of 1996. The cities' index of last May was 0.8 percentage
point higher than in same month last year, and 1.1 percentage
points less than the previous month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
