<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Envoy on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- British Special Representative
for Cyprus Sir David Hannay stressed here today that the only way
for an agreement on Cyprus issue is through "give-and-Take".
</P>
<P>
In a statement to reporters before leaving for Athens for
talks with the Greek government, after a three-day visit here,
Sir David noted that "give-and-take" is not a method, but common
sense and the only way that any negotiation can be brought to
agreements.
</P>
<P>
He said that the solution to the Cyprus issue will take time,
because the "subject matter is complex and the issue is sensitive".
</P>
<P>
However, Sir David expressed the hope that it will be possible
to make progress in the early rounds, and that later on there
will be "gradual progress" to arrive at a comprehensive solution
to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he is optimistic, Sir David said he was "very, very
pleased that after a long preparatory process, we have now
reached a point where the U.N. Secretary-General is resuming the
effort to get a formal negotiating solution through face to face
negotiations".
</P>
<P>
He was particularly pleased that the leaders of the two
communities are clearly happy to go along with that and the
governments of both Greece and Turkey are supporting the effort.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his meeting Tuesday night with Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash, Sir David described it as "useful".
</P>
<P>
The talks concentrated on the important issues: how to make the
direct talks, scheduled to begin on July 9 near New York, a
success; what will be the main subjects covered; what the main
pre-occupations on the Turkish Cypriots are; and how to overcome
these problems, the British envoy said.
</P>
<P>
During his stay on the island, Sir David also had two rounds
of talks with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides on Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Sir David's visit to Cyprus came one month ahead the
U.N.-sponsored direct talks between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
sides for a comprehensive solution to the protracted Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 after Turkish troops
occupied its northern third in the wake of an pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
This is his sixth visit to the island since Sir David was
appointed as British Special Representative for Cyprus in April
1996.
</P>
<P>
After his visit to Athens, the British envoy will fly on
to Ankara to meet Turkish government officials and possibly the
military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
