<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Manila-Singapore Ties Return to Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Singaporean Prime Minister Goh Chok
Tong today wound up his two-day official visit to the Philippines,
bringing to normal the bilateral relations which were almost
severed over the hanging of a Filipino maid in Singapore in 1995.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Goh and President Fidel Ramos explored ways
of strengthening bilateral relations and methods of enhancing
cooperation on trade and investment, socio-cultural projects and
infrastructure development among other concerns of common
interests.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed to work out an Action Plan to strengthen
the diplomatic, economic and cultural cooperation between the two
nations.
</P>
<P>
They also witnessed the signing of a memorandum of
understanding on cultural cooperation and three economic
agreements between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference after the talks, President Ramos
said the "turbulence" in Philippine-Singapore relations was
"finally over", adding the two leaders pledged to elevate their
countries' partnership to greater heights of cooperation and
mutual trusts.
</P>
<P>
Goh responded: "We are also glad that the period in our
bilateral relations is finally over. I, therefore, regard this
visit to the Philippines as a very important step towards the
reinvigoration of our ties."
</P>
<P>
The bilateral relations between Singapore and the Philippines
were strained in March 1995 after the hanging of Filipino maid
Flor Contemplacion who was found guilty of murdering a fellow maid
and a four-year-old Singapore boy. Angry Filipinos burnt
Singaporean flags and boycotted Singaporean goods. Manila withdrew
its ambassador to Singapore, which responded by doing the same.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said Singapore and the Philippines fully
restored their diplomatic relations due to the needs of their
political and economic interests.
</P>
<P>
Singapore and the Philippines were both founders of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN). After assuming
office in 1992, the Ramos administration turned the emphasis of
its diplomacy policy from the United States to ASEAN and has been
seeking a bigger role in ASEAN affairs.
</P>
<P>
However, its diplomatic disputes with Singapore became a
stumbling block. In the meantime, Singapore was also not
comfortable over the imbroglio. To play more positive roles inside
ASEAN, the two countries must first mend their cracked
relationship, especially when ASEAN is admitting Laos, Cambodia
and Myanmar in July to become a ten-member body which also
includes Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Both Singapore and the Philippines also noticed that poor
relations hampered their cooperation in trade and investments and
did harm to their respective economic development.
</P>
<P>
Singapore is a financial center in Southeast Asia. Its per
capita income is about 20 times higher than that in the
Philippines. As the country's third biggest trade partner,
Singapore accounts for some 5.6 percent of the Philippines' total
export.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Philippines is no longer "the Sick Man
of Southeast Asia". Its economy has recovered during the past few
years and grew by 6.8 percent last year. Industrial and
agricultural growth are performing well, inflation is slowing down
and financial situation is further improving in the country at the
present time.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said the normalization of bilateral relations
was also the outcome of joint efforts by the two governments.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has six million overseas workers in about 100
countries and regions. Cases of abuses against them have been
increasing in the past two years, prompting the Philippine
government to be more careful in resolving these cases.
</P>
<P>
Singapore, for its part, has adopted more measures to protect
some 80,000 Filipino workers in the city state.
</P>
<P>
Ramos and Goh broke the ice by agreeing to send their
ambassadors back earlier last year. In July last year, the
Philippine president took a further step, lifting the ban on
deploying Filipino workers to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon visited
Singapore, inviting Goh to visit the Philippines at any time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0062 </DOCNO>
