<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhujiang River linked up A Million Years Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Zhujiang River, one of the most
important in south China, existed as a major river one million
years ago, according to a Chinese geologist.
</P>
<P>
Yang Liankang, research fellow with the Ministry of Geology and
Mineral Resources, drew the conclusion after close study at the
section of linking-up site in Bose in southwest China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Yang discovered that 700,000-year-old crystal aerolites, which
were widely found in south China and Australia, were distributed
at the layer some 105 meters above the bottom of the river bed,
suggesting that the linking-up took place at least 300,000 years
before the formation of the layer.
</P>
<P>
Yang, who spent 151 days this year to tramp along the river,
also found that the origin of the river is at the highest peak of
Mount Maxiong in Qujing in southwest China's Yunnan province,
which is 2,443.9 meters above the sea level.
</P>
<P>
Previously it was thought that the river was initiated at the
mountain foot.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Yang found that the river mouth is not at Humen in
south China's Guangdong province but near Shekou to the south of
Humen, because the water to the south of Humen is still fresh.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the extending of origin and river mouth, the Zhujiang
River must be longer than the previously-thought 2,214 km, Yang
said.
</P>
<P>
Yang is the first Chinese scientist who has tramped along the
Yellow River and the Yangtze River. He has left his footsteps
along five of the seven longest rivers in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Price in Hong Kong Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The gold price in Hong Kong
