<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Needs to Redefine Visions of Development: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A representative of African
countries said at the Asia-Africa forum here today that "to better
orient development, African leaders will have to redefine their
own visions of development in order to improve living conditions
of their population."
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of African countries at the opening session
of the three-day Asia-Africa forum which began here today, Rwaka
Constance, permanent secretary of the Rwanda Foreign Ministry,
said although several African countries have embarked on political
and economic reform since 1994, the results are not yet
substantial.
</P>
<P>
She said, "foreign debts continue to increase to a level of 340
billion US dollars for the whole of Africa in 1996 which
represents 76 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) and 237
percent of the value of export."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she added, savings and investment rates are "far
below those of other developing countries in Asia and Latin
America, while direct foreign investment in all of Africa was only
4.5 billion dollars in 1996, or a mere 5 percent of the total flow
of investment to developing countries."
</P>
<P>
She said, "this forum is an important step towards finding the
means to develop African countries and to establish equitable and
sustainable partnership with the Asian countries which have
achieved remarkable social performances."
</P>
<P>
The forum, the second of its kind, will discuss lessons learned
from successful examples of Asia-Africa cooperation, Africa's
sustainable agricultural developments, food security,
capacity-building and private sector development.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 200 participants from 65 countries are participating.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of the forum will be for reference for the group 7
industrialized countries in their political and economic ties with
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The first Asia-Africa forum was held in Bandung, Indonesia, in
December 1994.  
</P>
</TEXT>
