<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Inflation Drops to 18.5 Percent by May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The level of Nigeria's inflation
eased further to 18.5 percent as of May from 29 percent last
year, according to Finance Minister Chief Anthony Ani.
</P>
<P>
This is also a drop from 23 percent in March this year, only
with the rate of drop lower than that of December to March which
declined by 5 percent from at the end of last year, according to
observers here.
</P>
<P>
Apart of a promising sign of economic growth, the new rate
also suggests possible realization of the government's projected
rate of 17 percent for this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
At a financial workshop held on Tuesday in Abuja, the Nigerian
capital, Ani said the economy recorded a fiscal surplus in 1996
and this year, stressing that it reflected prudent management of
resources which resulted in a growth rate of over 12 percent.
</P>
