<HEADLINE> Two More Nigerian Warships Sent to S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Two more Nigerian naval warships
have been deployed to Sierra Leone to reinforce the on-going
military intervention by the west African peacekeeping force
(ECOMOG) to flush out the coup leadership of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The additional warships, which were confirmed by the navy
authorities on Tuesday, underscored the seriousness of ECOMOG to
restore democracy in Sierra Leone, according to local press
reports today.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Commander A.M. Umar, a navy spokesman, said in a statement
that Nigeria's flagship NNS Aradu, an all purpose frigate, was one
of the two ships which left the country's territorial waters for
Sierra Leone on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
NNS Ekpe, a fast attack patrol craft, also left early Monday
to complement the arsenal of two other Nigerian naval ships NNS
Ambe and NNS Ekun already there.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear as of last night what specific instructions
had been given to these warships. However it might be a clear
message to the military junta in Sierra Leone led by Major Jonny
Paul Koromah that the Nigeria-led ECOMOG troops wanted nothing
short of total surrender.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations for peaceful resolution of the Sierra Leonean
crisis have been underway after the May 25 coup but so far no
report of any development is available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
