<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Mozambique to Cooperate in Crime Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Mozambique
will extend their crime combating cooperation through training of
detectives.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced yesterday in Pretoria by South
African Minister for Safety and Security Sydney Mufamadi, after
meeting his visiting Mozambican counterpart Almerino Manhenje.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi said the two countries had to share their limited
resources if they wanted to crush crime syndicates.
</P>
<P>
South Africa would grant Mozambique police access to a South
African detective academy currently being established, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said this will assist both the South African police service
and Mozambican police to stay abreast of world-class detective
methods.
</P>
<P>
Plans are also being made for the training of border control
officials from both countries.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi also said existing cooperation, particularly in the
fields of fighting against illegal weapon trafficking and vehicle
theft, had already resulted in many arrests and seizures.
</P>
