<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profit-Taking Forces Australian Sharemarket Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Afternoon profit-taking forced
the Australian sharemarket to a lower close today with market
leaders BHP, the major banks and major resource stocks all losing
ground.
</P>
<P>
The market retreated in the early afternoon after the all
ordinaries reached an intra-day record high of 2,635.7 shortly
before noon.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries closed 15.2 points down at 2,613.7 with
stocks in banking, development and construction, energy, food and
resources dipping.
</P>
<P>
"What we've seen very simply is an atmosphere of doubt that the
markets globally can't sustain the gains in the short term," Peake
Lands Kirwan's senior broker Bill Richmond said.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that despite a few fears among investors, the
market would continue its upward trend.
</P>
<P>
"I personally take the view that the markets can go a lot
higher," he said, adding that in the broad view, the all
ordinaries were only down about half a percent.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was down 11.8 points to 1,478.6, while
the all industrials index dropped 20 points to 4,089.9.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant Rio Tinto Ltd, however, went against the
general trend to gain 34 cents to 21.52 Australian dollars. The
company has announced a 20 million US dollar gypsum mine
development in Western Australia by Dampier Salt Ltd, of which Rio
Tinto owns 64.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
In other resource stocks, Australia's mining giant BHP lost 26
cents to 18.66 Australian dollars, Woodside Petroleum Ltd dropped
38.4 cents to 10.80 Australian dollars and WMC Ltd dipped seven
cents to close at 8.10 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, the four majors all lost ground, with
National Australia Bank losing 20.9 cents to 18.771 Australian
dollars, Commonwealth Bank dropping 20 cents to 14.30 Australian
dollars, Westpac falling 17 cents to 7.29 Australian dollars and
the ANZ declining 11.8 cents to 9.22 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was down 11.1 points at 1,553.0. Gold bullion in
Sydney closed at 343.45 US dollars an ounce from 344.35 US dollars
last.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 395.76 million shares traded worth
931.73 million Australian dollars (708.11 million US dollars),
with falls easily outnumbering rises 633 to 477.  
</P>
</TEXT>
