<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Population Commission to Hold General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Assembly
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The African Population
Commission announced here that its second general assembly will
be held here from June 16 to 19.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is jointly organized by the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), the United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa (UNECA) and the African Development Bank
(ADB), a press release issued by the OAU today said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to review the progress of the
implementation of the Dakar/Ngor Declaration on Population, Family
and Sustainable Development as well as the program of action of
the Interantional Conference on Population and Development with a
view to devising an appropriate strategy for the end of the
century and beyond.
</P>
<P>
The general assembly will also hear an activity report of the
outgoing chairman and deliberate on various issues related to
population activities in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from being the second most populous continent after
Asia, Africa has the highest population growth rate in the world.
Currently#,the regional population growth rate stands at about
2.9 percent per annum," the release pointed out.
</P>
<P>
It further said that coupled with other factors, the high
population growth rate places huge strains on the socio-economic
development of Africa, adding that the meeting is expected to
address these challenges and reflect on strategies for addressing
them.
</P>
<P>
The African Population Commission was established in May,
1994 at a meeting, which was attended by 48 OAU memebr states. It
came into being in order to encourage, coordinate and monitor
population activities in the region as a permanent continental
institution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
