The Turkish minister is expected to hand over today a message
from Turkish President Suleyman Demirel to his Egyptian
counterpart Hosni Mubarak, which reportedly dealt with the Turkish
military incursion into northern Iraq, the Egyptian MENA news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military movement in northern Iraq which started on May
14 has stirred Arab anger and world condemnation.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has previously sent a message to the Turkish leader
voicing his deep concern over the military operation.
</P>
<P>
Despite the statement by Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin
Erbakan Sunday that the Turkish army's 25-day-old operation in
north Iraq had come to an end, Iraq said it is still going on.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Turkish troops, backed by air power, poured into
northern Iraq on May 14 in a cross-border operation against the
outlawed Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK) bases which were used for
raids into southeast Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish operation was condemned by the Arab League
secretariat which demanded that Turkish forces withdraw immediately
for the sake of maintaining Turkish-Arab relations. 
