<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 09:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Supports UN's Resolution Demanding Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. committee's resolution
demanding Israel to pay compensation for damages in shelling of a
U.N. base in south Lebanon Last year reflected the international
will, Lebanese foreign minister has said.
</P>
<P>
An-Nahar, the most-circulated newspaper in Lebanon, quoted
today Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz as saying that the
"decision of the U.N. General Assembly reflected the international
will on both political and financial matters."
</P>
<P>
Boueiz's statement came in response to U.S. Department
spokesman Nicholas Burns' declaration Tuesday at a news briefing
that the U.N. General Assembly's Administrative and Budgetary
Committee has no authority to make the decision.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, the committee adopted a motion calling on
Israel to pay 1.7 million U.S. dollars for damages and casualties
inflicted on a U.N. peacekeeping force camp at the town of Qana
during the shelling of the compound on April 18, 1996.
</P>
<P>
A total of 107 countries voted in favor of the motion, when
Israel and the U.S. voted against it and Russia, Ukraine and
Japan abstained.
</P>
<P>
The money will be part of the 1997-98 budget of the
U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL).
</P>
<P>
Burns said the committee should not be allowed to direct "how
funds for a peacekeeping mission can be spent or cannot be
spent."
</P>
<P>
"It is simply beyond the competence of the committee to make
the decision that they took over the weekend," he said.
</P>
<P>
Details of the speeches delivered during the committee's
debate were released by the U.N. Tuesday, which confirmed that
the U.S. had threatened to link the vote to the renewal of the
UNIFIL's six-month mandate, which comes up for review next
month.
</P>
<P>
U.S. delegate Linda Shenwick was quoted as saying that "the
adoption on the draft would make it hard for Israel or the
United States to support the force."
</P>
<P>
"It would also make it difficult for the United States to
approve the extension of the UNIFIL's mandate next month,"
Shenwick added.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference Monday, Boueiz said Lebanon
"strongly rejects any attempt to link the issue of Israeli
compensation to the mandate of the U.N. peace keeping force in the
south (Lebanon)."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Capital Girds for HK Handover Celebration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- In the run-up to the celebrations
