</P>
<P>
Mountains of books about the region have appeared on shelves of
bookstores throughout the city, while exhibitions, concerts and
seminars on the theme cram listings of what's on in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Repair work on Beijing's thoroughfare, Chang'an Avenue, has
been completed 20 days before the big day. Meanwhile, workers are
installing new lights on Tian'anmen Square, where a mass gathering
will be held on the evening of June 30.
</P>
<P>
A sports stadium has been prepared for a huge performance on
July 1. Dancers and singers due to take part were busy rehearsing
yesterday when Beijing mayor Jia Qinglin and other high-ranking
officials came to inspect.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the smooth television broadcast of the extravaganzas
to every corner of the world, Beijing telecommunications workers
are busier than ever before.
</P>
<P>
"We have prepared 13 ground stations and nine transmittance
vehicles for the event -- that will provide a reliable service for
news organizations from more than 30 countries and regions. And 13
communications satellites will operate for the handover," said
Zhao Jidong, deputy director of the Beijing Telecommunications
Administrative Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the municipality has prepared enough fireworks to
make the handover night a colorful one. Among the fireworks
displays, some have been given special names like "the Flower of
Bauhinia," and "The Night of Hong Kong".
</P>
<P>
Residents have joined in pre-celebrations by singing songs and
reciting poems in the site of a ruined imperial garden -- Yu Ming
Yuan Park, on the city's northwestern outskirts which was
destroyed in 1900 by the Eight-Power Allied Forces, troops sent by
British, the United States, France and other Western powers, as
well as drawing paintings and playing dramas with the Hong Kong
theme.
</P>
<P>
Many Beijingers are flocking to museums where exhibitions are
being held to remind people of the history of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"In the last 12 days, we received some 50,000 visitors. The
number is unusual in the museum's history," said Guo Junying, an
executive from the Museum of the Chinese Revolution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
