<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Opposition Formed in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Three major Philippine opposition
parties today formally merged to form a united opposition front in
order to beat the powerful ruling Lakas-NUCD party in the May 1998
general elections.
</P>
<P>
A merger agreement was signed this morning by the leaders of
the Laban Ng Demokratikong Pilipino (LDP), the Nationalist
People's Coalition (NPC) and the Partido Ng Masang Pilipino (PMP).
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, a new opposition party called Laban Ng
Makabayang Masang Pilipino (Fight of Patriotic Common Filipinos)
will be formed after the merger, with Laban chairman Edgardo
Angara and NPC president Ernesto Maceda as its co-chairmen.
</P>
<P>
The new party will choose the opposition standard bearer, with
a full national and local ticket, for the coming May 1996 national
and local elections, the agreement said.
</P>
<P>
But the three parties failed to woo back the People's Reform
Party led by Senator Miriam Defensor-Santiago to join the united
opposition.
</P>
<P>
Defensor-Santiago pulled out of the merger talks late last week
after learning about an alleged agreement that the new united
opposition group will choose its presidential candidates only
between Angara and Vice President Joseph Estrada, who led the PMP.
</P>
<P>
But Angara told reporters after the signing ceremony that he
was optimistic that Defensor-Santiago will change her mind and
join the course of the united opposition later.
</P>
<P>
Angara denied there is such an agreement and promised the
selection process for the united opposition's presidential bet
will be fair and open to all presidential contenders.
</P>
<P>
He said the new party will register itself with the Commission
on Elections to become a formal political group after it convenes
on August 11 to formulate its constitution and other laws.
</P>
<P>
At the same press conference, Maceda, who is also senate
president, said his NPC party will not nominate any presidential
contender but his party will back up any presidential candidate
chosen by the united opposition.
</P>
<P>
Maceda said the new party will win the 1998 presidential polls
because it is "more than a match to the ruling Lakas-NUCD party."
</P>
<P>
According to Maceda, the new party controls 63 seats in the
278-seat bi-cameral Congress, 49 in the House of Representatives
and the rest in the Senate, and has the support of 35 provincial
governors and vice governors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Maceda predicted the governing party led by
President Fidel Ramos is facing the danger of break-up after the
Supreme Court Monday upheld its earlier ruling banning any charter
change to lift the term limit of Ramos through a people's
initiative.
</P>
<P>
With Ramos losing the chance of re-election because of the
court ruling, at least three presidential aspirants of the ruling
party will woo the endorsement of Ramos and thus a breakup of the
party is possible, Maceda said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0091 </DOCNO>
