<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Lionel Jospin took on Tuesday three measures to
fulfil the promises he made during the legislative campaign: the
regularization of the situation of thousands of paperless
immigrants, the freezing of a plan to build a railway between
Grenoble and Sisteron in southeastern France, and the designation of
an expert to solve the dispute over Renault's plan to close its
Vilvoorde auto assembly plant in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
-- France's European partners are studying the request by Prime
Minister Jospin to add a chapter on employhment in the Stability and
Growth Pact of the European Union (EU) monetary union. The Dutch
Prime Minister Wim Kok, who is now the president of EU, said Tuesday
in Paris that EU countries could reach a ``very elaborated''
agreement when ending their negotiations on the revision of the
Maastricht treaty during the Amsterdam summit to be held on June 16
and 17.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The government of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin has agreed to
re-examine the situation of tens of thousands of paperless
immigrants and some 40,000 illegal immigrants are likely to be given
the right to stay in France. The officials of prime minister's
office received a delegation of paperless immigrants Tuesday and
promised to study the files of some 100,000 irregular foreigners
case by case.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jacques Chirac Tuesday gave a hand to Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin by backing the latter's request to add a chapter on
employment and social models into the EU monetary Stability Pact.
While expressing his wish that the Stability Pact could be signed at
the EU Amsterdam summit this weekend, Chirac described the demand by
the Socialist government on further reflection on the pact as
``justifiable.''  
</P>
