<HEADLINE> Palestinian Minister Hails Egyptian Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Minister of Planning
and International Cooperation Nabil Sha'ath today praised efforts
exerted by Egypt to salvage the peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Voice of Arab radio, Sha'ath described
Egypt led by President Hosni Mubarak as the "honest guardian of
the Palestinian people's rights."
</P>
<P>
Egypt brokered a meeting between experts of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) and Israel here Sunday for the first
time in nearly three months in a bid to break the deadlock
caused by the Israeli move to build new settlement for Jews in
disputed Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
No breakthrough was made at Sunday's meeting, but the
Palestinian and Israeli negotiators agreed to meet in Israel
Thursday again to narrow the wide gap still dividing them.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Mubarak's Advisor Osama el-Baz will go to
Gaza and Tel Aviv to meet with PNA President Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu within the framework of
Egypt's sustained efforts to revive the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Sha'ath reaffirmed the Palestinian position on resuming the
peace talks through a freeze on the Jewish settlement building
including the controversial Har Homa construction on occupied
land at the outskirts of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians are ready to return to the negotiating
tables if Israel should show readiness to freeze settlement
activities, complete implementation of the Hebron agreement, open
checkpoints between the West Bank and Gaza and release
Palestinian detainees and prisoners," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has been pressing Israel for a three to six months halt
in settlement building to allow talks on a final resolution of the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict to restart.
</P>
<P>
The controversy over the Jewish settlement expansion policy
seemed to be deepening Wednesday as Netanyahu rejected the key
Palestinian demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
