<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Scientist Uses Fish to Kill Mosquitoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 11 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli ecologist has
invented a trap which uses an organic solution to attract
mosquitoes which then could be killed by gambusia fish.
</P>
<P>
According to The Jerusalem Report, a bi-weekly magazine, Tzvi
Horesh, a former founder member of the Society for the Protection
of Nature in Israel, has developed the Gambusia Mosquito Trap
which includes enough solution to keep the mosquitoes coming for
six months and four gambusia fish -- a tiny species native to
fresh waters of the eastern United States.
</P>
<P>
The trap -- an opaque plastic tank that must be kept out of
direct sunlight -- is supposed to keep a 100-square-meter area
mosquito free.
</P>
<P>
The fish, also known as the "mosquito fish" because of its
predilection for devouring the bloodsucking insects, require no
other food. They fall into a kind of coma in the mosquito-free
winter, and can be roused by brief exposure to sunlight when
summer comes around.
</P>
<P>
The trap has just gone on sale in Israel at a price of 197
shekels (some 58 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the firm marketing the trap said that the
precise formula for the magic solution is a closely guarded
secret. At present, the trap is for sale only in Israel, but
there are high hopes for marketing abroad in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
