<HEADLINE> Ramos Welcomes Court Ruling on Charter Change Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Ramos said
today he respected the final ruling of the Supreme Court
prohibiting a charter change movement aimed at extending the term
of the president.
</P>
<P>
The court Tuesday rejected a motion filed by the People's
Initiative for Reform, Modernization and Action (PIRMA), a
pro-Ramos group, for reconsideration of the group's petition to
amend the constitution.
</P>
<P>
"I respect the position taken by the justices and applaud them
for their commitment to the rule of law," Ramos said in a
statement issued during his visit to Clark with Singaporean Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong.
</P>
<P>
"We should now accept the Supreme Tribunal's decision, even as
we should have wanted a contrary ruling in order to uphold the
people's sovereign right as enshrined in the Constitution," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The PIRMA, launched late last year by Ramos' supporters, has
sought to remove the term limits for all government officials,
including that of the president, by changing the country's 1987
constitution.
</P>
<P>
The existing charter, which was promulgated after the downfall
of former dictatorial president Fernand Marcos, provides for a
single six-year term for the president.
</P>
<P>
Ramos himself has repeatedly indicated that he will step down
when his term of office expires in June 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
