<HEADLINE> Zambian Government Agrees to Meet Opposition Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has agreed
to meet opposition parties within three weeks in a bid to
facilitate sustainable democracy in the country, according to
Zambia Daily Mail today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made on Tuesday in Sweden, where
representatives from the ruling Movement for the Multi-party
Democracy (MMD) and several opposition parties attended a
roundtable meeting organized by the International Institute for
Democracy and Electoral Assistance.
</P>
<P>
The representatives reached agreements to systematically
approach the short, medium and long-term strategies for building
sustainable democracy in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The roundtable meeting held in Sweden is the first one between
the MMD and the opposition parties since the general elections
held last November.
</P>
<P>
The United National Independence Party (UNIP) led by former
president Kenneth Kaunda boycotted the elections in protest
against the constitutional amendment bill, which in fact barred
Kaunda from running for the presidency because his parents are
foreign immigrants. 
</P>
