<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Squeezes Further on Baht Punters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand apparently is
rushing more curbs on foreign speculators who are eager for the
baht to arbitrage, as its earlier bid to stabilize the baht
overseas seemed triggering a backlash on the local stock market.
</P>
<P>
The Thai central bank Monday imposed measures, what it called
temporary, to bar commercial banks and finance companies from
transferring unpaid shares to foreign accounts, or lending stocks
to foreign investors for speculative short-selling on the Thai
market.
</P>
<P>
It also required banks to use foreign currencies, instead of
the baht, to settle payments to the selling of shares by
foreigners on the Stock of Exchange of Thailand (SET).
</P>
<P>
The central bank introduced a tight baht policy to safeguard
the currency on offshore markets in late May, which successfully
drove the rate of the baht against the U.S. dollar down to around
23.90.
</P>
<P>
However, the policy made a big backlash on the local stock
market where speculators panically sold Thai stocks to obtain the
baht to arbitrage on a significant gap of the rate of the currency
against the dollar between the local and offshore markets, which
drove the SET index dive to an eight-year low last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign speculators converted their dollars into the baht
at the local exchange rate of 25.80 baht to buy Thai stocks and
sell them on the same day to cash in the baht and then shift the
money to offshore markets, like Singapore, where they could buy
back the dollar at 23.90 baht to make profits.
</P>
<P>
Some punters who do not have Thai stocks simply borrowed the
securities from Thai custodians.
</P>
<P>
In a latest circular sent to all banks and finance companies,
the Thai central bank urged the financial institutions to comply
with the new measures, warning that otherwise their foreign
exchange and other businesses will be affected.
</P>
<P>
The circular also said that Thailand has no policy to ban
foreigners from investing in Thai stocks and they were free to
trade and transfer the proceeds abroad but only in foreign
currencies.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Amnuay Virawan
stressed that Thailand had liberalized its financial sector to
help trading and investment, but not speculation.
</P>
<P>
The new measures would remain as long as they were needed, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government believed that its latest action could
contain the speculation on the baht on the local market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
