<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laid-off Workers Peddle in Street Markets (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Yang Xiaoying, a 40-year-old
woman, left home as usual at 7:00 am. But she didn't push her way
onto a crowded bus taking workers to a state-owned factory, she
got on her bike -- or rather trike -- and headed for a nearby
street market to sell garments.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago the woman worked in a sanitary products factory,
but it was forced to close due to poor management. The closure was
a crisis to her at first, but she created an opportunity out of it.
</P>
<P>
Stories like Yang's are not unusual in China these days.
Statistics show that although last year the Chinese government
arranged new jobs for more than two million laid-off workers, even
more redundant workers have to seek new job opportunities for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Yang rented a small stall, less than five meters square,
alongside Shidanan Lu in east Nanchang, the capital of southeast
China's Jiangxi Province, to sell a range of garments: coats,
trousers, T-shirts and belts.
</P>
<P>
"The business here is not bad, I have sold a few things this
morning soon after arriving," Yang said.
</P>
<P>
According to one of the street market management members of
staff, Guo Jiayuan, some 150 redundant workers have set up stalls
in the market. People call Shidanan Lu a "re-employment street
market."
</P>
<P>
"There are other seven other street markets similar to this one
in Nanchang, and the more traders there are, the cheaper it
becomes for everybody in terms of the taxes levied," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, an average of ten laid-off
workers each day have generated new sources of income for
themselves in these street markets, he added.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the situation two years ago when her factory had just
closed, Yang said that she felt as though the end of the world had
come. "But I soon realized that moaning wouldn't help me: I knew I
had to plan my own future out for myself as early as possible,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
While soliciting passers-by to make purchases, the woman
continued to talk. "I'm like everybody else with two hands -- I'm
hardworking -- I know that I can support myself."
</P>
<P>
Yang said that she was satisfied with her current job as street
market trader, and claimed to be earning twice as much cash as
she did when she was a factory worker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laid-off Workers Peddle in Street Markets (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to an official source, the majority of Nanchang's
90,000 laid-off workers have found new jobs themselves. Only
20,000 of them are employed in the state sector.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the provincial department of labor shows
that three-quarters of Jiangxi's 400,000 redundant workers have
regained job opportunities through their own efforts.
</P>
<P>
"Such community re-employment channels like the 're-employment
street market' have created many job opportunities for laid-off
workers," said Shi Zhongliang, the president of Jiangxi
Economic and Finance University and an employment researcher.
</P>
<P>
Some sociologists also note that "re-employment street markets"
as a phenomenon indicate an improvement in psychological
conditions of laid-off workers in China.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese workers who used to be secure at work in a life-long
employment system are now facing the reality of the market
competition situation," Qiao Jian, an expert on social relations
of employment, said.
</P>
<P>
Such "re-employment street markets" have also appeared in other
Chinese cities like Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
So far, in economically developed Shanghai and east China's
Jiangsu province, more than 400,000 laid-off workers have found
new jobs for themselves. In east China's Zhejiang province,
according to an official source, some 200,000 laid-off workers
will have to find new jobs themselves within the coming three
years.
</P>
<P>
Li Boyong, Minister of Labor, has spoken highly of the
self-employment effort by laid-off workers. He said that the state
will not play a major role in the re-employment process, and more
and more people will have to find jobs by competing in the jobs
market.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by the State Statistical Bureau shows that
in the next 15 years demand and supply of labor in China will
remain balanced, with 50 million, or one quarter of the total
employed population, being absorbed by non-public sectors.
</P>
<P>
At present the official unemployment rate in China is three
percent, and the figure will be controlled to under four percent
by the year 2010, a source from the bureau said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
