<HEADLINE> South Korea's First World Boxing Champ Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Kim Ki-Soo, South Korea's first
world boxing champion, has died of cancer at the age of 60,
according to news reports Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kim took the WBA junior middleweight title in 1966 from Italy's
Nino Benvenutti and retired in 1971. He died Tuesday of liver
cancer.
</P>
<P>
Born in Pukchong, North Korea, Kim won a gold in the welter
weight division in the Tokyo Asian Games in 1958 and also took
part in the Rome Olympics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
