<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Develop "Silicon Valley" in Inchon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A media valley, known as the South
Korean version of the "Silicon Valley", is setting out with the
development of a site in Inchon on its western coast.
</P>
<P>
According to the Inchon City and the Media Valley Planning
Committee, Inchon City is to reclaim offshore land of 3.49 million
square meters by February 1999 and start the construction of
infrastructure projects from the latter part of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The project is due to be completed in 2001 at a cost of 1.94
billion U.S. dollars. The total investment of the media valley,
which will consist of a software park, media park, media academy
and multimedia information center, is estimated at 4 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Inchon City will promote the software park as a base for
domestic and foreign software industries, selling the reclaimed
land at 136 dollars per square meter to companies which will set
up business there.
</P>
<P>
It will also make efforts to attract Asia Pacific Information
Infrastructure (APII) to the multimedia information center, which
is expected to build up as communications-supported headquarters
for a high-speed information communications network.
</P>
<P>
Inchon plans to take special measures to offer land in some
areas without cost in a bid to attract leading foreign companies
and venture businesses.
</P>
<P>
The project's planning committee and Inchon City said that
bringing in the world's leading high-tech firms would be crucial
to the success of media valley, adding that this would necessitate
the government's enactment of preferential policies. Incentives
offered to companies would include easing of administrative
regulations and tax reductions.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, companies wishing to move into the media valley
site include large-sized companies, such as Hyundai, Daewoo, LG,
Hansol and other mid-sized companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Petrol Prices Hiked in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The prices of petroleum products
were increased by 24 percent today by the Zambia National Oil
Company (ZNOC).
</P>
<P>
While explaining the price increase, a ZNOC spokesman said
that the earlier prices did not reflect the international prices
obtained in the market, and this had resulted in under recovery
costs by the company.
</P>
<P>
"There is also need to reflect the extra tax introduced in
this conversion of fuel levy as duty on the wholesale price," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The ZNOC hiked the prices of petroleum products in
December, 1996, by 15 percent due to the depreciation of the
local currency Kwacha against international currencies and the
increase of the international prices of petroleum products.
</P>
</TEXT>
