<HEADLINE> Uganda Releases 234 Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan authorities have
released 234 rebels of the West Nile Bank Front (WNBF), the New
Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
The freed WNBF members had surrendered since March this year,
the report added.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Colonel Nathan Katagara, the 409 Brigade Commander, said
at the releasing ceremony held in Arua, northwestern Uganda that
the government will create job opportunities for the released
through non-government organizations.
</P>
<P>
Donato Amabua, a local council official of Aura, asked the
former WNBF members to report to local authorities.
</P>
<P>
WNBF is a crippled rebel group which was acting in the
northwest and had bases in southern Sudan. Its main forces were
eliminated in southern Sudan by the rebel Sudan People's
Liberation Army in March.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report said some 200 remnants of WNBF joined the
Lord's Resistance Army, another rebel group of Uganda acting in
the north. Juma Oris, a leader of WNBF, is in exile in
Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
