<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali FM Withdraws from Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Foreign Minister Prakash
Chandra Lohani has withdrawn his support to Prime Minister
Lokendra Bahadur Chand's ruling coalition by tendering
resignation.
</P>
<P>
Lohani, who is from Chand's National Democratic Party (RPP),
told an urgently-called press conference here today that he had
handed his resignation to the prime minister to protest against
the crimes during the local elections last month.
</P>
<P>
Reading out his resignation letter at the press conference,
Lohani accused the prime minister of failing to protect the
interests of the National Democratic Party (RPP) in the local
polls.
</P>
<P>
However, it is not clear whether the prime minister has
accepted the resignation.
</P>
<P>
Main opposition the Nepali Congress (NC) has alleged that
workers of the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist,
CPN-UML), the biggest party of the ruling coalition, resorted to
widespread illegal activities including threat, intimidation and
rigging to secure a landslide victory in the local polls.
</P>
<P>
Lohani told reporters that Indian Prime Minister I. K. Gujral's
visit to Nepal last week caused the delay of his resignation.
</P>
<P>
He said that he joined the government three months ago at the
request of Prime Minister Chand, who is also the parliamentary
party leader of the RPP party.
</P>
<P>
Chand formed the present government with the participation of
the CPN-UML in March when he managed to topple a NC-led government
by withdrawing his party from the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Rumors here said that NC party leaders were making efforts to
lure away some ministers from the ruling coalition in order to
bring down the government.
</P>
<P>
The resignation of Foreign Minister Lohani, who held the same
post in the former NC-led government, indicated that Chand's
three-month-old government would face a crucial challenge in the
near future, political analysts here said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
