<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Omani Sultan's Special Representative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin said here
today that China is ready to forge a long-term, stable, and
comprehensive cooperative relationship with Oman for the next
century, on the existing basis of current bilateral links.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remark this morning during his meeting with
Thuwainy Bin Shihab Al-Said, a special representative of Oman's
Sultan Qabus Bin Said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that peace and development are the two major topics
facing the current world as it moves towards multi-polarization,
Jiang said both China and Oman are developing countries and that
they are concentrating their efforts on safeguarding peace and
developing their economies.
</P>
<P>
The two countries understand each other politically and their
economies are strongly complementary, thus leaving huge potential
for further cooperation, added Jiang.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that continued consolidation and development
of bilateral friendship and cooperation are in the fundamental
interests of the two peoples, and maintaining them will constitute
a contribution to both regional and world peace.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also briefed the visitors on China's accomplishments in
its reform and opening-up drive.
</P>
<P>
Oman and China have maintained good long-term cooperative
relations, Thuwainy said, and they have all along understood and
supported each other in both bilateral issues and those in
international arenas such as the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Oman thanks China for its political and economic support and
assistance, and hopes that there can be more progress to
benefit bilateral friendship and cooperation, added Thuwainy.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his country's early congratulations on the
coming return of Hong Kong, wishing China continuous development.
</P>
<P>
Jiang asked Thuwainy to convey his regards to Sultan Qabus,
saying that the latter was welcome to visit China at a time
convenient to the Sultan.
</P>
<P>
Thuwainy said that Sultan Qabus, who attaches great importance
to Oman-China relations, will be glad to accept Jiang's invitation
and realize a China visit as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Human Rights Stance Spelled Out in Oslo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OSLO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The President of the Human Rights
Society of China, Zhu Muzhi, today spelled out China's position on
human rights in a speech at the Norwegian Nobel Institute in Oslo.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, who heads a delegation from the Chinese human rights
research group, is making a four-nation European tour, which will
also take him to Sweden, Italy and Spain.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Zhu Muzhi called for dialogue to clear up
misunderstanding on the human rights issue.
</P>
<P>
"We have come to Norway this time because we hope to engage in
dialogue with various quarters so as to increase understanding,
clear up misunderstanding, learn from each other's strong points
to offset one's weaknesses in the interests of promoting human
rights," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that differences in the concept of human rights
and other values are only natural and normal since situations in
different countries vary.
</P>
<P>
"The only way to resolve the differences is through
constructive and earnest dialogue, not confrontation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted peace and development are the two most important issues
in the world today and are the issues that the Chinese people care
about most.
</P>
<P>
But when it comes to these two issues, some Western countries
do not know much about China and many misunderstandings exist, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"One rather common argument is that China's economy has been
developing but China is not democratic."
</P>
<P>
But in the view of the Chinese people, he said, developing the
economy is to fulfill the will of the people and economic
development is a manifestation of democracy.
</P>
<P>
"Some countries in the West stress democracy is an individual's
right to express one's views and pursue personal interests. We
believe individual rights are certainly not something that can be
dispensed with, but they are not the entire embodiment of
democracy. Things must be done according to the views and
interests of the majority of the people. That is democracy," Zhu
said.
</P>
<P>
"Human rights and democracy possess both universal and specific
characteristics. Countries face different situations and their
path to achieving democracy is also different.
</P>
<P>
"Today, many countries are following different roads and
practicing different models," he said.
</P>
<P>
The system of people's congresses that China has adopted is
appropriate to China's situation, he said. It guarantees Chinese
people's democratic rights to be masters of their own country and
brings them the greatest benefits.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that China has made rapid development shows that the
system of people's congresses is a democratic model suited to the
situation in China," the scholar said.
</P>
<P>
There is another argument in the West which maintains that
China's development constitutes a threat to other countries and
hinders world peace, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
The argument is also a consequence of a lack of understanding
of the actual situation in China, he said.
</P>
<P>
"China takes peace as a precondition for development. China
believes that without peace, there cannot be development."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, China is now trying hard to secure a peaceful and
stable domestic and international environment, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Proceeding from the groundless conclusion that China will
inevitably expand and pose a threat, some people advocate
containing China and not allowing China to develop. This attitude
is rather short-sighted and very dangerous," Zhu commented.
</P>
<P>
Containing China will lead to one of two possibilities. One is
that China cannot be contained and will continue to develop. In
this case, the party imposing the containment policy will
ultimately find itself the victim of its own policy.
</P>
<P>
The other possibility is that as a result of containment, China
once again falls into the tragic situation of poverty,
backwardness, disintegration and continued internal conflict.
</P>
<P>
It would certainly mean disaster for the Chinese people, but it
would do no good to the advocates of the containment policy and
the world at large, he warned.
</P>
<P>
"To begin with, the large Chinese market will disappear.
Hundreds of billions of U.S. dollars worth of trade will no
longer exist while millions and even tens of millions of
refugees will flood into the (outside) world," he said.
</P>
<P>
He asked for an objective assessment of China's human rights
situation.
</P>
<P>
The progress, or lack of it, in China's human rights
development should be viewed in a historical context. Whether
achievements are the dominant factor, or mistakes and shortcomings
are the dominating issues, the conclusion should be reached by
taking into consideration the overall situation.
</P>
<P>
"Assessment should not be made according to one particular
incident at a particular time. We believe that great achievements
have been made, but there are still many problems and efforts are
being made for further improvement. This is a fair assessment of
the situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China is not only sincere in improving human
rights within its territory, but also active in protecting human
rights internationally.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese people not only value human rights in their own
country but attach great importance to the safeguard and promotion
of international human rights.
</P>
<P>
"China has always respected the principles of promoting human
rights contained in the Charter of the United Nations and other
international documents regarding human rights, such as the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
"To date, China has signed seventeen international human rights
conventions. Within the year, China will also sign The
International Covenant on Economic, Social and Political Rights.
</P>
<P>
"China has been actively participating in UN human rights
activities and making her contributions to the promotion of
international human rights endeavors," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu's speech was applauded by the audience and was followed by
a question and answer session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
