<HEADLINE> Formula One Chief: Tobacco Ban to Cost Italy FI races </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Bernie Ecclestone, the Formula One
chief, says if it bans tobacco advertising, Italy would risk
losing both its Monza and Imola championship races.
</P>
<P>
"Italy will lose the two races, but without these sponsors all
courses are in danger of dying," the chief told the Turin
newspaper La Stampa.
</P>
<P>
La Stampa is controlled by the Agnelli family, which ones the
Ferrari Formula One team. The Ferrari team is heavily subsidized
by cigarette advertising. a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Ecclestone said the number of World Championship races in
western Europe could dwindle to just four from the present 12 if
teams lose tobacco company sponsors.
</P>
<P>
The anti-smoking movement in Europe picked up steam recently
when Britain's new Labor government pledged to ban tobacco
advertising.
</P>
<P>
Ecclestone has been waging a counteroffensive, warning of the
dire consequences for Europe of the loss of tobacco ads.
</P>
<P>
Italy has two championship races: the San Marino Grand Prix at
Imola and the Italian Grand Prix at Monza.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
