<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, India Sign MOUs for Cement Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Four private companies of Bangladesh
and India signed two Memorandum of Understandings (MOUs) here
Tuesday, under which two cement factories would be set up in both
countries, according to local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
The two joint ventures, each with an annual production capacity
of 100,000 tons, will be established in either Rajshahi or Sylhet
district of Bangladesh and Meghalaya of India, in order to meet
demands of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The MOUs signing ceremony was witnessed by ASM Quasem,
president of the Dhaka Chamber of Commerce and Industry (DCCI) and
HS Kumbhat, leader of the delegation of the Federation of
Industries of North Eastern Region (FINER) of India.
</P>
<P>
In his welcome address, the DCCI's President Quasem said that
the long common border between Bangladesh and India's northeastern
region was providing ample scope for closer trade and economic
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
As a result of trade liberalization policy in Bangladesh, India
has become one of the greatest beneficiaries with its increasing
exports to this country from 145.32 million U.S. dollars in
1989-90 to 1.1 billion dollars in 1995-96, Quasem said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Bangladesh's exports to India rose from 20.05
million dollars to 72.35 million dollars during the same time.
</P>
<P>
HS Kumbhat, also president of the FINER, now leading a
42-member delegation of businessmen in Bangladesh, also expressed
the hope that the signing of MOUs would pave the way for further
cooperation in trade and business between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Both Bangladeshi and Indian businessmen could study other
feasible areas like agro and mineral based products, plywood and
veneer, fresh vegetables, fruits, fish and fish products, poultry,
newsprint and fertilizer, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
