<HEADLINE> SKorea Expects More Active Trade With Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 11 (Xinhua) -- South Korea is expecting Hong Kong
to be more active in trade with it after Hong Kong's return to
China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's trade with China and Hong Kong, which stood at 17
billion U.S. dollars and 11.5 billion dollars respectively, is
estimated at 25 billion dollars and 14 billion dollars this year,
according to reports from the Ministry of Trade, Industry and
Energy (MOTIE) and the Korea Chamber of Commerce and Industry
(KCCI).
</P>
<P>
The reports said Hong Kong will see a steady economic growth
after it returns to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The territory's economy is expected to grow 4.3 percent in
1998, 5.4 percent in 1999 and 5.9 percent in 2000, higher than 3.6
percent in 1995, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
South Korea expects China with Hong Kong to solidify its
position as the third biggest trade partner after the U.S. and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
South korea's trade with China and Hong Kong is expected to
reach 40 billion dollars and 18 billion dollars in 2000, while
that of the U.S. and Japan will amount to 75 billion and 70
billion dollars, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
