<HEADLINE> G-7 Economic Summit to Focus on Africa and Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Promoting economic development
in Africa and integrating Russia into the global economy will be
the major goals for this year's annual economic summit of G-7,
U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said today.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the world's seven richest industrial countries --
the U.S., Japan, Germany, France, Britain, Canada and Italy --
will hold the 23rd summit in Denver on June 20-22. Russian
President Boris Yeltsin for the first time will join the
discussions from the beginning of the summit.
</P>
<P>
"In an era of globalization where national borders no longer
define the boundaries of economies, we can use our position to
encourage the free flow of goods, capital, technology and
ultimately wealth across the globe," he said in a speech prepared
for delivery to the summit.
</P>
<P>
On Africa, he said the Denver summit is expected to explore
ways to alleviate poverty by promoting economic growth and trade.
</P>
<P>
"Approximately 600 million people or one-tenth of the world's
population have yet to fully participate in the global economy and
reap the benefits of integration," Summers said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that "the deepening of Russia's engagement in the
summit process reflects Russia's increased stature on the world
stage and its heightened commitment to work in close partnership
with the seven."
</P>
<P>
The summit leaders would also review efforts to reduce threats
to global financial markets to prevent future financial crises
such as the one that engulfed Mexico when it was forced to devalue
its currency in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
Summers said that the Clinton administration would use this
summit to showcase the opportunities presented with the end of
the Cold War and spread of free markets around the globe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
