<HEADLINE> Fugitive Sicilian Mafia Boss Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A suspected leading drug trafficker
of the Sicilian Mafia was arrested Monday in France in a joint
French-Italian police operation after two years on the run, police
said today.
</P>
<P>
In the latest of a string of arrests netting top fugitives of
Cosa Nostra, Francesco Paolo Albamonte, 35, was detained in
Toulon, a southern French port, after a tip-off from Italy's
paramilitary police.
</P>
<P>
Albamonte was suspected to be a leading lieutenant of jailed
Mafia "super boss", Salvatore "Toto (the beast)" Riina, in charge
of a cocaine smuggling ring with South American countries.
</P>
<P>
He did not put up resistance while being found at a gas station
in central Toulon. French police found false documents and
identification papers with him, which had allowed him to travel
through European and South American airports.
</P>
<P>
Albamonte allegedly controlled Riina's international drug
operations including quality control at production and
transport. The international arrest warrant said he was involved
in an international drug ring dismantled in Britain several months
ago.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Italian police arrested a suspected No.2 Mafia
leader, Pietro Aglieri and two other fugitive convicted killers in
Palermo, Italy. These are the latest blows to Cosa Nostra in a
police campaign starting from the capture of Riina in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
