<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House of Representatives to Vote on Flag Amendment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- As the U.S. House of
Representatives set to vote on a constitutional amendment banning
flag burning Thursday, a poll indicates most Americans favor such
a measure.
</P>
<P>
"This amendment has received resounding support around the
country," said Rules Committee Chairman Gerald Solomon, who
co-authored the amendment. He said the measure, with 285
co-sponsors, will reach the House floor Thursday, two days before
Flag Day.
</P>
<P>
The recent telephone survey showed that 81 percent of
registered voters would vote for a constitutional amendment to
protect the flag from desecration and burning, Neal Rhoades of
Wirthlin Worldwide told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
To become part of the Constitution, an amendment must win
two-thirds majorities in the House and Senate, followed by
ratification by three-quarters of the states.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court in 1989 ruled that burning the U.S. flag is
protected free speech, invalidating statutes in 48 states.
Congress then passed a law protecting the flag, but the Supreme
Court found that unconstitutional in 1990. Then Congress tried but
failed to get two-thirds majority votes for a constitutional
amendment.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the House passed, 312-120, an amendment to let
Congress and the states establish laws protecting the flag, but
the Senate fell short, 63-36.
</P>
<P>
This year's amendment, which cleared the House Judiciary
Committee on a 20-9 vote on May 14, would give only Congress "the
power to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag of the
United States."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
