<HEADLINE> Hungary to Seek More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Hungary will continue to
encourage foreign investment regardless of the outcome of the 1998
general election, Prime Minister Horn Gyula said here today.
</P>
<P>
Hungary wants to establish long-term cooperation with foreign
investors who have already set up projects in the country and that
his government will be open to proposals, he told a foreign
investment conference in the capital.
</P>
<P>
One of the government's main priorities is to speed up
infrastructure development across the country, he told the
meeting, attended by senior government officials and domestic and
foreign business executives.
</P>
<P>
Privatization has now been completed in the main sectors of the
economy and agriculture, which has been in severe difficulties
over the last few years, should now start to recover later this
year or early next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Privatization Minister Csiha Judit told conference delegates
that Hungary has attracted foreign investment totaling 16 billion
U.S. dollars over the last few years, of which five to six billion
dollars came through privatization.
</P>
<P>
The acquisition of state enterprises by foreign investors has
been a major feature of Hungary's privatization process.
</P>
<P>
But she said that although the program had drawn close to an
end, remaining state properties would not be sold off at bargain
prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
