<HEADLINE> Nepal Seeks National Consensus on Treaty with India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government is seeking
a consensus among major political parties over its 1950 treaty
with India, which is expected to be reviewed by the two
governments within two months, the local press here said today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Kumar Gyawali has written letters to the
political parties asking them for recommendations on the question
of reviewing the 1950 Nepal-India Peace and Friendship Treaty,
newspapers reported.
</P>
<P>
The letters to all parties represented in parliament were sent
out last Sunday, one day after Indian Prime Minister I. K. Gujral
concluded his three-day official visit here, according to a
Foreign Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
During his recent stay in Nepal, the Indian prime minister and
his Nepali counterpart Lokendra Bahadur Chand directed that all
bilateral issues including those relating to the 1950 treaty be
discussed at the next foreign secretary level meeting within two
months.
</P>
<P>
However, the Nepali side is still perplexed with what exact
clauses of the treaty should be reviewed although the two
governments have agreed to review it after Nepal's persistent
demand during recent years, sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal and India agreed for the first time in early 1995 to
review the controversial treaty after criticism arose from all
sides in Nepal describing the treaty as outdated.
</P>
<P>
Critics here said that some of the treaty's clauses infringe on
Nepal's sovereignty and also fail to reflect the changing times.
</P>
<P>
The treaty provides for special bilateral relations between the
two countries. For example, citizens of one country should be
given national treatment in the other one when conducting economic
activities and they should enjoy privileges in residence,
ownership of property and participation in trade and commerce.
</P>
<P>
India earlier had maintained that the 1950 treaty would either
be retained entirely or abolished in accordance with its
provision, ruling out any possibility of revision.
</P>
<P>
With the no-revision provision of the 1950 treaty, Nepal and
India might review the treaty and turn it into a new one which
requires ratification by parliament, a high-ranking Foreign
Ministry official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sofia to Host Atlantic Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Sofia will be the first capital
outside the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) to host an
Atlantic Treaty Association (ATA) meeting, it was announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
Sofia, the capital of Bulgaria, will hold the 43rd annual ATA
meeting from October 4 to 7, as agreed upon by mayor Stefan
Sofianski and visiting ATA Secretary-General Alfred Kaen,
according to a Bulgarian Telegraph Agency report.
</P>
<P>
Kaen, who arrived here yesterday for a two-day visit, said the
choice of Sofia as the host is a proof of positive assessment of
Bulgaria's efforts to join NATO, the report said.
</P>
<P>
He assured Sofianski that it is his belief that if Bulgaria
would not be among the first batch of applicants to join NATO, it
could be among the second.
</P>
<P>
ATA, founded in 1954, is a non-governmental organization to
make the public be aware of NATO's purposes and objectives. The
Atlantic Club of Bulgaria is an ATA member.
</P>
<P>
The Sofia Meeting is expected to be attended by some 350
participants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
