<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Battlefield Turns to Tourism Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The city of Puqi in central China's
Hubei province, where the famous Battle of Chibi was fought during
the Three Kingdoms period (220-280), is boosting tourism.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of this year, the city played host to
268,000 tourists, with revenues reaching 64 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
During the recent Chibi Culture and Tourism Festival, another
48 overseas travel agencies set up links with the city to promote
business, and 25 tourism development projects were signed,
involving a total investment of 2.78 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Chibi Battle, resulting in the defeat of a large number of
troops led by Cao Cao, by the lesser-populated military units of
Sun Quan and Liu Bei, was decisive in creating the three kingdoms
of Wei, Shu, and Wu. The battle is frequently cited as a textbook
example of military tactics.
</P>
<P>
Puqi has built an exhibition hall highlighting the story. Also
constructed were a number of tourism facilities such as hotels and
shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, the city has spent 86 million yuan
in developing 22 tourist projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0160 </DOCNO>
