<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Curb Violent Protesters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has decided to
take tough actions against protesters who use violent or illegal
means to gain concessions for their demands.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at the weekly cabinet meeting Tuesday
among growing concern over violence by protesters who at times
laid siege to government buildings or blocked highways in defiance
of the law, according to local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Interior Ministry at all levels nationwide
have been ordered to take action whenever and wherever protesters
resorted to violent or illegal means.
</P>
<P>
Protesters who wanted to bargain for something would have to
gather in an orderly manner or send representatives to negotiate
with officials, Thai Interior Minister Sanoh Thienthong was quoted
as saying by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that there had been a total of 63 protest
demonstrations in the past five months around the country,
including a mock one staged by textile workers recently to show
how to use homemade grenades and Molotov cocktails at work places
or government agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
