<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Could Be Largest Basketball Market: NBA Boss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SALT LAKE CITY, June 10 (Xinhua) -- As some 650 million people
around the world watched the Chicago Bulls to be tied by the Utah
Jazz in the NBA finals, NBA commissioner David Stern is looking
further beyond the Pacific Ocean for the future.
</P>
<P>
"I think, China could develop the largest basketball market in
the world," Stern told Xinhua in an interview on Monday during the
1996-97 NBA finals here. "And sometime in the next four or five
years we may hold a NBA regular season game in China.
</P>
<P>
"Before the regular game goes there, we may have some
exhibition games in China."
</P>
<P>
The NBA boss still remembered his first visit to China in the
year of 1989 when he made the first TV contract with China's
nationalwide TV station -- the CCTV. And the NBA games soon
attracted a lot of fans in the country.
</P>
<P>
"That's what really happened in the United States, and the same
thing we experienced in Europe. When more NBA games on television,
people, especially young children, became to love it every where
in the world." Stern said.
</P>
<P>
Stern, who became the NBA commissioner in 1984, has guided the
league to chang "from a small business to a business all around
the world."
</P>
<P>
The total NBA revenue equals 192 million U.S. dollars in 1984
while the gross retail sales of NBA products was over 30 billion
U.S. dollars in the 1996, according to NBA Properties release.
</P>
<P>
Stern considered the largest population of 1.2-billion people,
the rapid development of economic and the improvement of people's
living standards as the three main factors for China to build its
own basketball pro-market.
</P>
<P>
China has been dominating Asian basketball for the last two
decades. The Chinese men's team just made a breakthrough to take
the ever best eighth place in the Atlanta Olympic Games. The
Chinese women's side was silver medalist both at the 1992
Barcelona Olympic Games and the 1994 world championship.
</P>
<P>
During halftime interval at the NBA finals game two last
Friday, Stern called from Chicago to Hong Kong to greeting a NBA
Finals Party which was attended by some 150 local reporters.
</P>
<P>
"That was the only place I called during the Finals and I even
had a video message to the people there before the game started,"
said Starn, who believed that the Asian, especially China, is the
most important goal in NBA's development of international
initiative.
</P>
<P>
NBA has opened offices in Hong Kong, Tokyo, Melbourne and other
oversea cities.
</P>
<P>
Stern thought the handover of Hong Kong to China on July 1
would bring NBA closer to China.
</P>
<P>
"We've already had very good relationship with the Chinese
Basketball Association (CBA) and we looking forward to increase
the relationship betwee the NBA and CBA," Stern said.
</P>
<P>
China has started two professional men's basketball leagues in
the last two years and Starn believed "the CBA and NBA can work
with each other to arrange visits" by teams from both sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
