<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Laos Agree to Promote Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Laos agreed in
principle to issue new border passes to facilitate tourism, trade
and investment between the two countries, according to a Thai
Foreign Ministry source.
</P>
<P>
The two sides would issue new one-year permanent border passes
to the local people and seven-day temporary border pass to the
non-locals, Pitsanu Chanvitan, director of the Thai Foreign
Ministry's East Asia Department, was quoted today by local press
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The issue was raised for discussion during a senior officials'
meeting of the two countries in Vientiane last week.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, border pass holders can stay on either
side of the border for three consecutive days and the holders of
permanent ones would be allowed to have their passes extended.
Holders of temporary passes would not be allowed to seek an
extension.
</P>
<P>
The permanent border pass will facilitate the promotion of
trade and investment, said Pitsanu.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Foreign Ministry is planning to initial a similar
agreement with Cambodia within this week and the new agreement
will come into effect after 90 days of the signing date.
</P>
<P>
The agreements will be signed during Thai Prime Minister
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh's visit to Vientiane and Phnom Penh on July
20-22, Pitsanu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
