<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Panamanian government and the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) have earmarked 70 million U.S. dollars
for health, education, housing and public works projects in Panama.
</P>
<P>
Some 28 projects are currently underway through the joint
efforts of the UNDP and the Panamanian government. The biggest
projects being carried out is to promote investments in different
social sectors. The UNDP's biggest priority is to eradicate
poverty in Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan exports of meat, sausages, preserved
meats and subproducts totaled 200 million dollars during the first
five months of this year, a 22 percent of increase over the same
period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to figures from the National Meat Institute in
Uruguay, the revenues earned from beef sales accounted for 80
percent of the total of the meat sector while lamb accounted only
for 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico's financial sector received more than 1.5
billion dollars of direct foreign investment during the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
Mexico received the lion's share for its financial sector among
Latin American countries, with 28 percent of total foreign
investments in the region.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Deposits in Argentina set a record in May with
more than 60 million dollars, 28 percent higher than last year.
</P>
<P>
According to figures published by the Fundacion Capital, 49.2
percent of the total was peso deposits and 50.8 percent dollar
deposits.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- During the first five months of this year, the
mineral water market in Chile increased 30 percent more than the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Higher purchasing power contributed to the increase since per
capita income in Chile rose from 1,438 dollars to nearly 5,000
dollars during the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica's inflation was just 0.51 percent in
May, the lowest in the past four years in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
