<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Investment Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's foreign investment
dropped 36 percent in the first five months this year to 13.7
billion U.S. dollars from 18.38 billion dollars in the
corresponding period of last year, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
However, "there is nothing to worry about because what has been
achieved so far has exceeded the achievement in the last five-year
development plan (1990 to 1994) period," State Minister for
Investment Affairs Sanyoto Sastrowardoyo said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to officials at the Investment Ministry today,
Sanyoto attributed the drop of foreign investment to the effect of
the May 29 general election in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Investors take a wait and see stand to see which party emerges
as the winner in the elections," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said he believed the situation would recover by
around November as had happened five years ago in the 1992
election.
</P>
<P>
During the 1992 elections, investment dropped around 40 percent
compared with 1991.  
</P>
</TEXT>
