<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Economy Grows Fast In Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Jilin Province in northeast
China is making the most of its grain production, animal
husbandry, and farm produce and by-products processing, to bring
agriculture to a higher level.
</P>
<P>
The province, one of China's major grain producers, set a
record high in grain production last year with 23.2 billion kg,
and its farmers had 2,100 yuan of annual income per capita, up 30
percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Good harvests for years running have in turn promoted livestock
raising as well as agricultural products processing.
</P>
<P>
Its animal husbandry produced 11 billion yuan in output value
last year, and increased the value of more than five billion kg of
maize, a significant proportion of which was consumed by
animals. As a result, Jilin raised 18 million pigs to have enough
meat for people in the province, and some to spare for sale
outside Jilin.
</P>
<P>
The province, although known as a granary in north China, was
short of meat, and had to import pigs from south China. But now it
has become an important pig production base, and sells pork
elsewhere on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
Jilin is increasing efforts to turn grain resources into
profit, and has invested more than a billion yuan into developing
farm produce and by-products processing industry.
</P>
<P>
Its starch, alcohol, seasonings, and other products now take a
lion's share of the domestic market, and have begun to sell on the
world market. A company mainly engaged in chicken production
collected two billion yuan in sales value last year, with exports
totaling 70 million US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
