<HEADLINE> Protection Force to Protect Election Observers in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Italian-led multinational force
(MPF) in Albania will guarantee the safety of international
observers who will monitor the nation's June 29 elections.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made here today at a meeting of the MPF's
ruling committee, comprised of representatives from the eight
countries that form the 6,000-strong force.
</P>
<P>
The force will also help with the lodging of around 600
observers who will be sent by the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to oversee the poll, informed
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Albania is to hold elections in a bid to end the crisis in the
country following an anti-government rebellion earlier this year
triggered by the failure of bogus investment schemes.
</P>
<P>
The ruling committee also agreed to recommend to the
U.N. Security Council the extension of the MPF's presence in the
troubled Balkan republic for another 45 days.
</P>
<P>
Although the multinational force is sponsored by the OSCE, its
current mandate, which expires on June 28, is authorized by the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Council is expected to make a decision around June 26 on
whether the force will continue to stay in Albania after the
elections, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
