<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Cold Wave Threatens Coffee Harvest in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian coffee harvests
could be affected by a recent cold wave in the southeastern state
of Minas Gerais, the biggest coffee-growing region in Brazil, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
Low temperatures are continuing and may produce the same
phenomenon occurred in 1994 when extremely cold weather affected
the 1995 production. Coffee production fell by 15.8 percent
between 1994-95 after dropping from 2.6 million in 1994 to 1.9
million tons in 1995, the Brazilian Institute of Geography and
Statistics said.
</P>
<P>
The "El Nino" phenomenon was first observed in the country in
February, causing heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
The state of Minas Gerais produces half of the coffee grown in
Brazil which is the world's largest coffee producer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Recognizes HK SAR Passports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand will recognize the
new Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) passports, said
Foreign Minister Don McKinnon today.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, he announced that the SAR passport will be
treated the same as the existing British National Overseas
passports used by many Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
"These documents will be accepted around the world," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the New Zealand Immigration Service said in a media
release today that it will be business as usual for Hong Kong
people wishing to visit or live in New Zealand after China resumes
the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1.
</P>
<P>
General Manager Chris Hampton said the service's Hong Kong
office will remain open and continue to process visa applications
in the same way as it does at present.
</P>
<P>
"Our approach accepts the 'one country, two systems'
philosophy," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
