<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Vaccine Offers Hope for Skin Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- An effective treatment for the
most deadly form of skin cancer, melanoma, could be on the horizon
after promising tests on a vaccine by Melbourne researchers.
</P>
<P>
In a recent trial, the vaccine halted or reversed the progress
of melanoma in more than 50 percent of patients with an advanced,
and usually fatal, form of the disease, local newspaper the Age
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough, to be unveiled at a melanoma conference in
Sydney today, could offer the first real hope of conquering a
disease that kills almost 1,000 Australians a year.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine was jointly developed by researchers at the Ludwig
Oncology Unit at the Austin Hospital and scientists from Belgium
and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Professor Jonathan Cebon, director of the Ludwig unit, said the
European scientists had identified a series of proteins present on
melanoma cells which, when injected back into the patient,
stimulated an immune response that attacked the cancer.
</P>
<P>
The Melbourne researchers, working with the European
scientists, tested the proteins, which are called antigens, in
patients with advanced melanoma.
</P>
<P>
They found that the immune response was particularly strong
when the melanoma antigens were injected back into the patients
with a hormone known to enhance the immune response.
</P>
<P>
Out of 28 patients in the trial, two experienced complete
remission, two had partial remission and in 11 the progress of the
disease was halted. Thirteen of the patients progressed to more
serious disease and death.
</P>
<P>
Professor Cebon said the vaccine-hormone treatment may be more
effective against melanoma in its early stages than when the
cancer had already spread.
</P>
<P>
The professor predicted clinical trials of a melanoma vaccine
within a decade.
</P>
<P>
Success against melanoma would probably be achieved by a
combination of vaccines and other immune-enhancing therapies, in
the same way that HIV patients were showing improvements with a
cocktail of drugs rather than a single type of treatment, he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
