<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Attitude on Human Rights, Immigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan's support for Australia's
push into Asia has been thrown into doubt by Canberra's handling
of sensitive issues such as human rights and Asian immigration, a
top Japanese official was quoted today as saying.
</P>
<P>
The comments by a senior adviser to Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto are the first signal that Japan is imposing
conditions on its support for Australia in key Asian political
forums, an unprecedented move in the post-war relationship, the
Australian Financial Review reported.
</P>
<P>
Until now Japan has been the most consistent supporter of
Australia's drive for a greater political role in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The official, from the Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs,
made it clear that Australia's handling of issues, such as
Australia's opposition to Myanmar's entry into the Association of
Southeast Asian Naitons (ASEAN) and belated government's response
to the immigration debate sparked by MP Pauline Hanson, had
prompted the change in attitude.
</P>
<P>
Debate among senior Japanese officials about Australia's
attitude to Asia had also prompted a significant change in the key
speech delivered by Hashimoto during his visit to Australia in
April, removing references to Australia's tradition of "liberalism
and democracy".
</P>
<P>
The official said Australia could not rely on Japan's
unqualified backing for its participation in the Asia-Europe
Meeting forum (ASEM), the key group for political and economic
dialogue between Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
ASEM brings together the leading Asian and European economies
and has become a touchstone for measuring Australia's success in
seeking greater engagement with Asia, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed surprise at the way in which the debate over
Pauline Hanson's comments has been allowed to drag on and not
dealt with quickly by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
The official referred to Australia's opposition to Myanmar's
entry into the ASEAN as an example of the greater sensitivity
required in dealing with Asia.
</P>
<P>
"We were embarrassed when Australia opposed Myanmar's entry
into ASEAN and the way it was handled," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
