<HEADLINE> China's PC Giant Floats Shares in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The local arm of the China Great
Wall Computer Corp., the largest PC manufacturer in the country,
issued 57 million shares today in Shenzhen, south China's
Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
The Great Wall Shenzhen Co., Ltd. is expected to raise 364
million yuan with each share valued at 6.58 yuan. The fund will be
used for research and product development in hardware and software
and to strengthen the footholds of its series of personal PCs on
the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
China Great Wall owns 64.05 percent of Great Wall Shenzhen's
stock. It has grown into China's biggest PC development center and
is capable of producing annually 400,000 PCs, one million
monitors, two million power plugs, three million sets of card and
board.
</P>
<P>
China sold 2.1 million PCs in 1996, 10 percent of which were
made by the Great Wall Shenzhen Company. Chinese brands dominated
China's PC market in 1996, taking 56 percent of the market share.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen Company has been active in international economic
and technological cooperation and has set up three joint ventures
with IBM to produce PCs, electronic card and board, and other
products.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen Company will increase purchases of major
components for making PCs from big international companies such as
Intel and IBM, according to company officials .
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen Company expects to yield 72.57 million yuan in
profits this year, an increase of 16.5 percent over last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
