<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Gas Begins to Be Piped into Beijing Kitchens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Another 6,000 Beijing families
yesterday began to cook food with natural gas, which means less
exhaust smoke and cleaner kitchens.
</P>
<P>
The environmentally-friendly gas is piped into Beijing from
North China Oilfield in the capital's neighboring province of
Hebei.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the year, 100,000 households using coal gas now
will have their gas fittings adapted to burn natural gas,
bringing the clean gas to 550,000 Beijing households, Wu Liya,
vice-director of the Beijing Public Utility Bureau, was quoted as
saying by today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
More than one million families will be natural gas users by the
end of 2000, when the city will be supplied with 850 million cubic
meters of the gas annually.
</P>
<P>
Enough natural gas from Shaanxi Province is expected to arrive
in Beijing by September 30, via an 860-kilometer pipeline, to
supply 80 percent of the city's needs.
</P>
<P>
The North China Oilfield, yields 500,000 cubic meters of
natural gas daily, promised to guarantee needs for natural gas
from Beijing before the influx from Shaanxi.
</P>
<P>
The first gas storage tank for civilian use is expected to be
ready by the end of 2000. The 100-million-cubic-meter tank will be
located underground at the North China Oilfield. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
