<HEADLINE> US Sends Team to Brazzaville </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
dispatched a military assessment team to Brazzaville in the Congo
in case an evacuation of Americans is requested, the Pentagon said
today.
</P>
<P>
Fight broke out on June 5 in Brazzaville, the capital of the
Republic of Congo, pitting soldiers backing President Pascal
Lissouba and their militia allies against ex-President Denis
Sassou Nguesso's militia. According to the Pentagon, the situation
in the capital "is quite chaotic."
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said the team of about a dozen
communications specialists, security troops and planners arrived
in Brazzaville this afternoon on a C-130 military transport from
Germany.
</P>
<P>
There are believed to be some 60 Americans in Brazzaville. Some
of them would be taken out of Brazzaville on the C-130, Bacon
said. 
