<HEADLINE> Britain Urges N.Irish Group to Be Calm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Facing a rising tension in Northern
Ireland over pro-British parades, British Secretary of Northern
Ireland Mo Mowlam today urged local people to calm down to avoid
possible violence.
</P>
<P>
"It is up to everybody to try and cool it. Things are very
tense at the moment," she told reporters after a session of talks
involving most of the province's parties in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Pro-British loyalists, angry at a police ban on annual
Protestant parades through a nearby Catholic village, injured 27
police officers last Saturday and tried to burn down a Catholic
church at Harryville on the outskirts of Ballymena town, causing
tension in the area.
</P>
<P>
Catholic nationalists in Belfast, who wish to separate from
Britain and merge into the Irish Republic, have demanded the
abolition of anti-riot plastic bullets, blamed for the deaths of
14 civilians during years of strife, after Britain said some
stocks had been withdrawn in April because their velocity was too
high.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam said there must be no repeat of widespread conflict last
year over the parades. "It is up to the people of Northern Ireland
to help us to avoid that happening," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Irish Republican Army's political wing Sinn Fein has been
barred from multi-party negotiations since last year because it
insists on a military campaign to end the British rule of Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
But Britain's new Labor government last month ended a 16-month
ban on low-level official contacts with Sinn Fein after a lull in
IRA violence, giving the Northern Ireland peace process some new
hope. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
