<HEADLINE> US Supports Loan to Croatia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. will support a loan of
13 million U.S. dollars from the International Finance
Corporation, the private sector arm of the World Bank, to Croatia,
the State Department said today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. decided to back the loan because of recent actions by
Croatian President Franjo Tudjman that met demands set down by
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, State Department
Spokesman Nicholas Burns announced.
</P>
<P>
Burns told reporters that the U.S. government has decided not
to block the "very modest loan."
</P>
<P>
He cited the fact that Tudjman had opened a long-closed bridge
at Brcko between Croatia and Bosnia and ordered the arrest of
several people suspected of brutalizing elderly Serbs who tried to
return to their pre-war homes in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
Tudjman last weekend publicly committed Croatia to inter-ethnic
reconciliation and to making sure that Serbs had a place to live
there in Eastern Slavonia, Burns added.
</P>
<P>
"Now that we've seen concrete positive steps, not just words,
by the Croatian government and by Tudjman personally, surely we
want to send a positive signal that this is the kind of action
that will warrant support from the West," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
But he added that if Tudjman did not follow up on his
commitments, the U.S. would act to block future loans and
assistance, including a much larger World Bank loan.
</P>
<P>
During her trip to the Balkans, Albright warned both Croatia
and Serbia that they will not get aid from the U.S. unless they
fully comply with the Dayton peace accords. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
