<HEADLINE> US FAA Requires Airline Cargo Fire Suppression </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government today asked
all airlines to install fire detectors and extinguishers in the
cargo compartments by 2001.
</P>
<P>
The rule would affect about 3,000 U.S. commercial airliners,
the Federal Aviation Administration said.
</P>
<P>
Most airline cargo compartments already have detectors and
extinguishers, but that equipment has not been required for sealed
compartments.
</P>
<P>
It was assumed that lack of oxygen would extinguish any fires
that might break out in those areas.
</P>
<P>
Investigators believe that a cargo of oxygen generators in a
sealed compartment fed the fire in the ValuJet plane, leading to
the deadly crash in 1996 in Florida that killed 110 people.
</P>
<P>
The National Transportation Safety Board has pressed for new
rules on the equipment, and the Air Transport Association
announced that its members would install the equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
