<HEADLINE> OHR: Serbs to Lose Aid by Obstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Office of High Representative
(OHR) warned Bosnian Serbs today that their obstruction of the
country's common institutions might cost them international
assistance.
</P>
<P>
The warning came after Serb representatives' absence forced the
postponement of the sessions of the Council of Ministers and the
Bosnian parliament. The two sessions were originally scheduled for
today and Monday respectively.
</P>
<P>
The reason behind the Serbs' failure to show up at the joint
institutions was that they have backtracked from the economic laws
which they agreed last month, according OHR spokesman Colum
Murphy.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of those economic laws is the pre-condition for
holding a donors' conference on Bosnia and because of the
agreement on the package of laws by all parties in Bosnia, the
conference was scheduled on June 24-25.
</P>
<P>
Despite the likeliness that the laws might not be approved by
the Bosnian parliament, the donors' conference will still be held
as scheduled, Murphy said, adding that the Serbs would be
penalized for their obstruction.
</P>
<P>
Those who meet the demands by the international powers will
receive financial assistance and "those who do not cooperate will
not," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
