<HEADLINE> Albright: Frank Talks With China Serves US Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has said what the United States should do with
China is to make frank dialogue rather than to sever the trade
relations by revoking the Most Favored Nation status.
</P>
<P>
She made the remarks in an article published in today's
Washington Post, as the annual congressional debate concerning
China's trade status is under way.
</P>
<P>
"The administration is convinced our interests are better
served by a frank dialogue with China in which differences are
aired and opportunities to establish common ground are explored,"
the secretary of state said.
</P>
<P>
She reminded those who opposed the extension of China's MFN
status that one of every five human beings on this earth lives in
China who would move forward no matter what kind of oppositions
were confronting them.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever the outcome of the debate (over China's MFN status),
China will be a rising force in Asian and world affairs," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Albright warned those opposition factions in Congress "not to
let the differences voiced in the current debate obscure agreement
on long-term goals."
</P>
<P>
She said revoking the MFN status would not only do harm to
China, but also affect "U.S. exports, endangering more than
170,000 high-paying American jobs."
</P>
<P>
Besides that, higher tariffs on low-cost Chinese imports would
add more than 500 million dollars to America's shopping bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
