<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Plans to Sell Stingers to South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon said today that it
planned to sell 1,065 "stinger" anti-aircraft missiles and 213
launchers to South Korea for 307 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon said in an announcement that it was the first such
kind of deal with South Korea, intended to help South Korea
"develop a defense capability with an ability to protect itself
from unwarranted aggression."
</P>
<P>
Stinger, fired by a single soldier with the launcher resting
on a shoulder, find and track targeted aircraft or helicopters
after launch. They are made by the Hughes Missiles System Co., a
unit of General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
The United States is the largest military supplier to South
Korea and the sale of Stinger was the latest deal of weaponry.
</P>
<P>
In defending the sale, State Department spokesman Nicholas
Burns said it "makes sense" for U.S. policy on the Korean
Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"We have to take very seriously the security of South Korea.
It's imperative that South Korea have the most modern weaponry
available to defend itself, along with the 37,000 (American)
troops there," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crash Recording Device for Air Bags Urged in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National
Transportation Safety Board today recommended the development of a
crash recording device to store information about auto accidents
in a hope to prevent more deaths from deploying air bags.
</P>
<P>
The board called for the modification of the computer sensor in
air bags to allow safety officials to retrieve data about crash
speeds and air bag deployment.
</P>
<P>
Board officials said the device would work like the black boxes
that record information about airplanes in flight.
</P>
<P>
Board officials want to know more about the severity of
crashes, air bag deployment as well as seat belt usage. They want
to document cases of successful air bag deployments so better air
bags can be designed.
</P>
<P>
Deploying air bags has been blamed for the deaths of 40
children and infants and 27 adults in accidents they should have
survived.
</P>
<P>
The deaths from deploying air bags were in low-speed accidents
and in most cases the other occupants in the car suffered only
minor or no injuries. Most air bags are designed to deploy in
head-on crashes of 12 mph or more.
</P>
<P>
There are 60 million cars on the road in the country today with
air bags that are not safe for everyone, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Notified on Conventions Applying to HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador Wang
Xuexian today sent to UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan
notifications and a list of 16 international conventions that will
apply to Hong Kong from July 1.
</P>
<P>
Wang, acting permanent representative of China to the UN, said
in his notifications that in accordance with the Sino-British
Joint Declaration signed on 19 December 1984, China will resume
the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong with effect from July 1
1997. Hong Kong will become a special administrative region from
July 1.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Sino-British Joint Declaration and the
Basic Law of Hong Kong, the international conventions, to which
China is a party, will apply to Hong Kong from July 1 after
consultations with authorities of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region; the international conventions or
agreements, to which China is not a party but which are
implemented in Hong Kong, may continue to be implemented in the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region from July 1.
</P>
<P>
The list of 16 conventions sent to the UN chief today is the
second batch of the conventions that will apply to Hong Kong from
July 1. Wang sent the notifications and list of first 24
international conventions that will apply to Hong Kong on June 6.
</P>
<P>
In the new list of 16 conventions that will apply to Hong Kong
from July 1, China has acceded to six. They are as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- the International Convention on the Elimination of All Forms
of Racial Discrimination;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of
Discrimination against Women;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention against Torture and Other Cruel, Inhuman or
Degrading Treatment or Punishment;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention on the Rights of the Child;
</P>
<P>
-- the United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in
Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances; and
</P>
<P>
-- the Basel Convention on the Control of Transboundary
Movement of Hazardous Wastes and their Disposal.
</P>
<P>
The 10 conventions and agreements in the list, to which China
is not a party but which are implemented and may continue to be
implemented in Hong Kong, are as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- the International Agreement for the Suppression of the
"White Slave Traffic" of 18 May 1904;
</P>
<P>
-- the International Convention for the Suppression of the
White Slave Traffic of 4 May 1910 and the Protocol Amending the
International Agreement for the Suppression of the White Slave
Traffic, signed at Paris on 18 May 1904, and the International
Convention for the Suppression of White Slave Traffic, signed at
Paris on 4 May 1910, of 1949;
</P>
<P>
-- the Supplementary Convention on the Abolition of Slavery,
the Slave Trade, and Institutions and Practices Similar to Slavery
of 7 September 1956;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention on the Political Rights of Women, opened for
signature on 31 May 1953;
</P>
<P>
-- the Slavery Convention of 25 September 1926 and the Protocol
of 1953 to amend the convention;
</P>
<P>
-- the International Convention for the Suppression of the
Traffic in Women and Children of 30 September 1921;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention on Consent to Marriage, Minimum Age for
Marriage and Registration of Marriages, opened for signature on 10
December 1962;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention relating to the Status of Stateless Persons
of 28 September 1954;
</P>
<P>
-- the Agreement for the Suppression of the Circulation of
Obscene Publications of 4 May 1910 and the Protocol amending the
same agreement of 4 May 1949; and
</P>
<P>
-- the International Convention for the Suppression of the
Circulation of and Traffic in Obscene Publications of 12 September
1923 and the Protocol to amend the same Convention of 12 November
1947.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador also asked the UN secretary-general to
notify all parties to the conventions on the decisions of the
Chinese government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
