<HEADLINE> Greenpeace to Sue UK Gov't Over Atlantic Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The environmental group Greenpeace
said today it would take the British government to court if the
government decides to open up Atlantic waters for oil exploration.
</P>
<P>
"Greenpeace has given the Department of Trade and Industry 10
days in which to respond before the matter is lodged before the
High Court requesting leave for a judicial review," the
environment group said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace sent a letter to Trade and Industry Minister
Margaret Beckett today, protesting against the government's
alleged failure to apply European Law in the Atlantic frontier
north of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
"Greenpeace believes that the government has failed to apply
the European Habitats Directive in relation to cold water coral
and the Environmental Impact Assessment Directive," the statement
added.
</P>
<P>
It also called on the British government to suspend exploration
licenses awarded under the 17th offshore oil licensing round.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the Atlantic Frontier oil development is damaging,
unnecessary and illegal," Greenpeace Deputy Executive Director
Chris Rose was quoted by local media reports as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Trade and Industry had reportedly promised to
respond to the letter in the next few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
