<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Chancellor Kohl Meets Chinese Leader Li Ruihuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl met
here today with visiting Chinese leader Li Ruihuan, both stressing
the need to further strengthen bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Li, Chairman of the National Committee
of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, Kohl
said that Germany attaches great importance to the German-Chinese
relations.
</P>
<P>
Although there were some twists and turns last year between the
two countries, the bilateral relations have witnessed improvement
again, he added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Europe is making efforts to speed up the
integration process while China is undergoing sustained and rapid
economic development, Kohl said that to improve and expand the
bilateral relations is in the interests of the two countries and
the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan conveyed to Kohl the cordial regards from Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng. He also conveyed Li
Peng's invitation for Kohl to visit China.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan said he was greatly delighted to visit Germany on the
eve of the 25th anniversary of the establishment of the diplomatic
relations between China and Germany.
</P>
<P>
He said that through the visit he has become more aware of the
profound social foundation and broad prospects for the Sino-German
friendship.
</P>
<P>
He said there exist no problems left over from the history, nor
conflict of interests, between the two countries. Rather, China
and Germany share extensively common interests in economy and
other fields, he added.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China can draw on Germany's advanced technologies and
use as reference its managerial experience.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Chinese government attaches importance to its
relations with Germany and hopes to further their comprehensive
cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Sino-German relations in general are good,
as they have returned onto the track of healthy development after
experiencing twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
In expanding bilateral relations, he said, leaders of the two
countries have played an important role. He said the Chinese
government especially appreciated Chancellor Kohl's unique
contributions to promoting Sino-German ties and the
far-sightedness and vision he showed in handling international
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Kohl expressed his agreement with Li's views. He also asked Li to
extend his regards to Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li
Peng, and accepted Li Peng's invitation to visit China. Kohl said he
is looking forward to meeting Chinese leaders again. He last visited
China in 1995, his fourth trip to the country since he became German
chancellor in 1982.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Li briefed Kohl on China's current economic
situation and on Hong Kong's return to the motherland. They also
exchanged views on international issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is on a seven-day official goodwill visit to Germany, met
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel Monday, and is scheduled to meet
German President Roman Herzog and Rita Suessmuth, president of the
Bundestag, the lower house of the German parliament, Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
