<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Troops Continue Evacuation From Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- French troops today continued to
evacuate foreigners, mostly French nationals, from the Congo
Republic's Brazzaville to Libreville in Gabon, while fighting
resumed between the two warring factions.
</P>
<P>
Fifty foreigners were evacuated on board a French military
transport aircraft from the airport of Brazzaville, after French
troops evacuated 700 others on Monday, French military officers
said.
</P>
<P>
Fighting between government troops and the militiamen of former
President Denis Sassou-N'Guesso continued only 50 meters from the
French soldiers at Brazzaville's international airport. But the
French were not threatened, said Alexis Jaraud, spokesman for the
French troops.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 850 French soldiers, including 400 foreign
legionnaires and 400 elite parachutists, were supposed to complete
their deployment in Brazzaville after flying from Chad and
military bases in southern France.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese government today assured France that there was no
anti-French hysteria in Brazzaville, and asked Frenchmen to stay.
</P>
<P>
"No xenophobic feeling is developing in Congo. The relations
between Congo and France remain the best," the national radio of
Congo said.
</P>
<P>
It said: "The movements of the French troops on the Congolese
territory are known and authorized by the Congolese
authorities. No military action of the French troops is directed
against the people of Brazzaville and the interests of the
Congolese people."
</P>
<P>
The French government also encouraged Frenchmen to stay at home
in Brazzaville, because their properties could be looted during
their absence.
</P>
<P>
The Gabonese President, Omar Bongo, who is a close friend of
Congolese President Pascal Lissouba, and the father-in-law of
Sassou-N'Guesso, is trying to mediate a ceasefire with the support
of French President Jacques Chirac, who personally intervened last
night asking the warring sides to stop fighting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
