<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Consolidation Seen in Banks, Securities Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 10 (Xinhua) -- BankAmerica Corporation announced
Monday that it is buying Robertson, Stephens &AMP; Company, a San
Francisco investment firm, which is seen as another thrust by
commercial banks into investment banking.
</P>
<P>
This is also the latest evidence of a trend--consolidation
among banks and securities firms--gathering momentum.
</P>
<P>
Two months ago, the Bankers Trust New York Corporation agreed
to buy Alex. Brown &AMP; Sons, the oldest stock brokerage in the
United States, for about 1.7 billion U.S. dollars. Then in
mid-May, the Swiss Bank Corporation agreed to acquire Dillon, Read
&AMP; Company. A New York investment company, for about 600 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
With more consolidation occurring among banks and securities
firms, many financial experts concluded that the wall that was
thrown up between commercial and investment banking in the
Depression was "definitively breached".
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. Congress has for more than a decade debated
whether to repeal the glass-Steagall Act of 1933, which bans banks
from underwriting stocks, rulings by the Federal Reserve and
other regulators have given commercial banks permission to perform
virtually all of the functions of a brokerage firms, according to
a report of the New York Times today.
</P>
<P>
After BankAmerica buying Robertson, Stephens investment firm,
executives from financial services expected to see more
consolidation, particularly among the larger banks and securities
firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
