<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Namibia Pledge Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Namibia
today signed in Pretoria a defense cooperation agreement with the
two sides expressing the wish to promote exchanges in military
fields.
</P>
<P>
South African defense minister Joe Modise and his Namibian
defense minister Philemon Malima participated in the signing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The agreement formalized several forms of cooperation between
the armed forces of the two countries, Malima told reporter after
the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward assistance from the South African
national defense force... in areas including our ground forces,
maritime wing, our air force," he said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that peace was a prerequisite for economic
development, Modise also hailed the cooperation agreement with
Namibia as crucial to statiblity in the region.
</P>
<P>
Referring to African situation, both Modise and Malima
expressed concern over continuing conflict in Africa, saying that
the civil conflict in Congo and Sierra Leone have raised fears of
Africa remaining an unstable continent.
</P>
<P>
Malima expressed the hope that Namibia and South Africa would
help restore peace in Congo as they did in Zaire, now the
Democratic Republic of Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
