<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Hopes Holbrooke to Help Resolve Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government said it hoped
U.S. special envoy for Cyprus, Richard Holbrooke, to help ensure
that talks on the Cyprus issue not be used as a pretext for
"obstructionism", government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said today.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on statements made by Holbrooke concerning the
possibility of conflict between Greece and Turkey, Reppas said the
Cyprus issue was the "touchstone" for the improvement of
Greek-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that all sides must approach the problem with
responsibility and show real interest in finding a solution.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Financial Times on Monday, Holbrooke
said that the situation in Cyprus could deteriorate at any moment,
bringing Greece and Turkey into direct conflict.
</P>
<P>
The envoy said that a solution could open the way for a "great
historical rapprochement" between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and the Turkish-
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash have agreed to hold direct talks in
New York in July. On the same day Clerides will go to Greece to
coordinate their policies before the start of the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
