<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Volume of daily transaction in the Beirut Bourse has
increased about 150 times in only 14 months since its opening,
Ghabriyal Sahnawi, chairman of the Beirut Bourse Committee, was
quoted by the Al-Hayat daily Tuesday morning as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that the average volume of transaction now has reached
nearly 3 million U.S. dollars a day from 20,000 dollars at the
beginning, and the number of exchanged shares has reached 300,000
a day, compared with only 30,000 of 14 months ago.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli defense firms are negotiating some 10.5
billion U.S.dollars worth of contracts with foreign clients and
expect more than half to be signed by the year 2000, The Jerusalem
Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The pro-government English daily quoted Ilan Biran, Defense
Ministry director-general as saying that more than 60 percent of
the contracts are being negotiated with clients from the Far East
and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Ilan Biran said at a news conference in Tel Aviv Monday that in
1996 Israel signed contracts that totaled 2 billion dollars, and
this year, it has so far concluded more than 1 billion dollars in
contracts.
</P>
<P>
Currently the second most active area is Western Europe,
where Israeli firms are negotiating nearly 1.4 billion dollars
of contract, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
The potential lies more in Eastern Europe, where officials
expect to win contracts of 1.47 billion dollars by the year
2000. North America is expected to collect close to 700 million
dollars in defense contracts within the next two to three years.
</P>
<P>
Biran said that he hopes the Israeli defense firms will
cooperate with each other abroad and embark on joint marketing
and manufacturing ventures. This, he said, would eliminate
inefficiency and needless competitions.
</P>
<P>
Military sales are a major foreign currency earner for
Israel. The country's large defense industry has suffered much
in recent years, due to a fierce competition at the shrinking
post-cold war market.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has signed a contract with the U.S. for the
purchase of 1 million tonnes of wheat because of the global wheat
price drop, Egyptian Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Some 165,000 tonnes of wheat will arrive in Egypt by July, and
the rest in the end of November.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Fast Fashion Fair, a specialized international trade
exhibition of clothing, footwear and fashion accessories, will
open on June 12 at the newly-opened International Merchandising
Center (IMC) in Nicosia, Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 companies will exhibit top fashion brands from around
the world, including France, Italy, the U.K., the U.S., Greece and
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Exhibits include clothes for adults and children, lingerie,
sportswear, evening and bridal wear, footwear, fashion
accessories, as well as furs.
</P>
<P>
Buyers from the Middle East, North Africa, the Balkans, Russia,
Greece and Cyprus, have been invited to attend this event, which
will last until Sunday, June 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
