<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Minister on Labor Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- China today urged the International
Labor Conference to pay more attention to the social and economic
development level of most International Labor Organization (ILO)
members when formulating labor standards.
</P>
<P>
"For developing countries which constitute the overwhelming
majority in the membership, the existing labor standards, taken as
a whole, do have the defect of being excessive in number and in
criteria," said China's Labor Minister Li Boyong at the 85th
session of the International Labor Conference held here on June
3-19.
</P>
<P>
"At present, many countries, particularly developing countries,
are yet to ratify more standards, this is not because of the lack
of political will, but rather as a result of their limited
capabilities," Li said.
</P>
<P>
The key to solving this problem lies in more economic
development and better labor legislation so the ILO should provide
its members with more effective technical cooperation and
assistance that are tailored to their actual needs, he said
</P>
<P>
Li expressed China's opposition to the two proposals of the
"social labeling" and the introduction of some type of new
mechanism in addition to strict supervisory procedures.
</P>
<P>
"The labeling of one country's products as up to labor standards
is, in essence, tantamount to openly advocating the rejection of
products from other countries," Li said.
</P>
<P>
On the new mechanism, Li said pointed out that the nature of
this proposition is to force members who have not ratified the
standard to undertake the same obligations as those that have
ratified.
</P>
<P>
"This is not consistent with the provisions of the ILO
constitution, " said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese official appealed to ILO to concentrate on
increasing employment and eliminating poverty while pushing for
the setting of labor standards.
</P>
<P>
"Only in this way can the organization live up to the
expectations of its members and better rise to the challenges of
the 21st century, " he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
