<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference of Balkan Foreign Ministers Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The two-day conference of Balkan
foreign ministers ended today in the northern Greek port city of
Thessaloniki with a joint communique.
</P>
<P>
The "Thessaloniki Declaration" stressed the ministers'
resolution to actively promote relations of "good neighborliness,
stability and cooperation" in the region.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed their commitment to work together for the
rapid development of the region, placing particular emphasis on
the liberalization of trade and structural programs.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed to review a proposal for the creation
of an international forum aimed at promoting good neighborly
relations.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers said they support Albania's efforts to
re-establish political stability.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to establish a regional centre based in Turkey for
the promotion of trade and supported the expansion of the
activities of the Bucharest-based Balkan centre for cooperation
between small-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos said "we are now
beginning to talk about our problems among ourselves, without the
mediation of foreigners."
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed to meet again in Turkey next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
