<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Draws up Plans to Avert Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Disaster
Prevention and Preparedness Commission today announced that it
has drawn up plans to prevent and ward-off any sudden flooding
disaster that might surface in the future.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, at a one-day meeting
on the exchange of experiences in flood prevention and
containment, the commission said the plan includes pre-disaster
prevention, post- disaster measures and rehabilitation, adding
that the plan has taken into consideration the strong and weak
points of the measures taken during the flooding which hit
several parts of the country last year.
</P>
<P>
The commission estimates that 450,000 people could be exposed
to flooding this year.
</P>
<P>
According to experts of the meeting, the swollen Tana lake and
tributaries of the lake as well as Gilgel Abay last year flooded
farm lands in Amhara region. Crops over 6,000 hectares of land in
the region were destroyed and 15,000 people displaced. The Awash
river and its tributaries flooded 3,895 hectares of farm lands,
killed 374 animals and displaced 58,000 people in Oromia region
last year. While in the southern people's region, 18 people were
killed and 47,000 inhabitants displaced as well as 136 animals
flooded over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts of the meeting said the major causes for the flooding
last eyar were deforestation and soil erosion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
