<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Criticizes U.S. for Holding Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed Al-Sahhaf criticized the U.S. for holding the food and
medicine contracts submitted to the U.N. Sanctions Committee, the
Iraqi News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent Monday to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
Al-Sahhaf said the U.S. representative to the Sanctions Committee
behaved with motives "far from the humanitarian objectives."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. representative recommended the committee to hold the
contracts signed by Iraq and foreign companies under the
"oil-for-food" deal, claiming that the items included in these
contracts were not listed within Iraq's purchase and distribution
plan, according to the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf said that the contracts included 10 for medical
supplies, one for French wheat and another for sugar from the
United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the country's need for wheat and sugar, two
essential materials in the purchase and distribution list,
saying that the U.S. representative had approved similar
contracts for the supply of the two items on previous occasions.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister asked the U.N. Secretary-General to
intervene personally in the Sanctions Committee to expedite
smooth processing of the contracts signed by Iraq and foreign
companies under the "oil-for-food" deal.
</P>
<P>
He also requested that his letter be distributed as a
U.N. Security Council document.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and the U.N. signed last year the "oil-for-food"
deal, which allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of
oil over six months on a renewable basis to buy food and other
daily necessities.
</P>
<P>
The deal, which expired on June 7, has been renewed for
another six months, allowing Iraq to sell another 2.1 billion
dollars of oil.
</P>
<P>
However, all the contracts signed between Iraq and foreign
companies must be approved by the Sanctions Committee consisting
of representatives of all the 15 Security Council members, before
they are conducted.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S., a permanent Security Council member, remains
deeply suspicious of Iraq. It insists that the U.N. imposes tight
controls to make sure the supplies are distributed fairly and not
used for military purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
