<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Coup Leaders Demand 46 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Sierra Leonean coup leaders are
demanding 46 million U.S. dollars to step down and allow the
return of outsted civilian president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, a report
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a source close to the leaders of the May 25
coup as saying in Freetown today that the money will be shared by
about 35 soldiers and rebels of the Revolutionary United Front,
who have allied with the army since the coup.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's ambassador to the United Nations, James Jonah,
said on Monday that the coup leaders wanted money to give up
power, but director of defense information, colonel Abdul Sasey
had denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
"There have been no negotiations concerning money," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports also said that a delegation of the coup
authority had visited Cote d'Ivoire and is expected to arrive in
Ghana today for negotiations on peaceful solutions to the current
crisis caused by the coup. 
</P>
