<HEADLINE> SADC Countries Urged to Realize Energy Plan of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Southern African
Development Community (SADC) member countries today were urged
speedier realization of the energy plan of action for
sustabinable development in the region.
</P>
<P>
Opening a four-day 22nd SADC energy officials' meeting in
Arusha, Northern Tanzania today, the Principal Secretary in the
Ministry of Energy and Minerals, Patrick Rutabanzibwa, emphasised
that member states should concentrate on the energy plan of
action for the benefit of the whole region.
</P>
<P>
"Securing a stable supply of energy is a vital pillar for
maintaining sustained economic growth. We see the results in the
Asian region where rapid economic growth has occured and energy
demand had risen sharply," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Rutabanzibwa also called upon SADC members to make efforts in
developing alternative sources of energy that would reduce the
burden on women and children and protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
Instead of concentrating only on electricity related projects,
he exhorted renewable energies such as solar and efficient
technologies that will reduce strain on forests and environmental
degradation.
</P>
<P>
He also paid tribute to SADC Technical and Administration Unit
(TAU) for co-ordinating energy activities in the region.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Regional Co-ordinator of SADC energy sector,
Antonio Da silva, said the signing of the Southern African Power
Pool (SAPP) two years ago by member states except Mauritius, was
the final critical step in the establishment and implementation
of the project.
</P>
<P>
He informed the meeting that important activities have already
been undertaken for the operationalisation of the power pool.
"The power pool will constitute the most important instrument for
the development co-operation in the electricity sub-sector for
the coming years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Da Silva told the participants that the Democratic
Republic of Congo (former Zaire) has become a formal
co-operating partner of SAPP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
