<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot FM Stresses Urgent Need for Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides today underlined the urgent need for a settlement to
the Cyprus question, likening the problem to a dormant volcano
which could explode at any time.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his departure for a three-day official visit to
Japan, Kasoulides said the complacency which prevailed over the
years and the indifference toward the need for a settlement must
be dealt with "because the Cyprus question is a factor of
instability in the Eastern Mediterranean."
</P>
<P>
"What we have been saying for a long time that Cyprus is a
dormant volcano likely to erupt, has now been accepted, as I
gather from statements made by U.S. Presidential Emissary
Richard Holbrooke," Kasoulides said.
</P>
<P>
This, he added, "reassures us that the international
community will be interested more actively than in the past in
the need for a settlement."
</P>
<P>
The newly-appointed U.S. Presidential Emissary for Cyprus
Holbrooke told the BBC World Service Monday that the situation
in Cyprus could "explode one of these days in a gigantic tragedy
which will embrace other countries in the region."
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said Holbrooke's assertion is that a pending
Cyprus problem could create disruption and conflict in a region
where peace and stability are the main objectives.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the forthcoming U.N.-sponsored direct
negotiations, likely to take place on July 9 near New York, the
minister acknowledged that the Greek Cypriot side will be under
pressure during the talks, but "the more we base our positions
on international law and human rights principles the more
difficult it would be for others to exert pressure on us to
accept notions that are, for us, unacceptable," he added.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is expected to issue
invitations to President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash for face-to-face negotiations after
three-month U.N.-led proximity talks between two sides on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops occupied its northern
third in the wake of a short-lived coup seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
After his visit to Japan, Kasoulides will fly to Moscow for
an official visit and hold talks with Russian officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Parliament Reviews Iran-EU Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Parliament today reviewed
the on-going diplomatic crisis between Iran and the European
union (EU) as well as the future prospects.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA reported that members of the
Parliament Foreign Policy Commission and Iranian ambassadors to EU
states stressed on safeguarding of Iran's foreign policy
principles based on the dignity, philosophy and expediency of
the Islamic system.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Iranian ambassadors to EU states
maintained that relations between Iran and European states
should be based on mutual respect and due regard for each
other's cultures and religious sanctities.
</P>
<P>
It said that the meeting studied a report on the latest
developments in Iran-EU diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
However, it gave no detail on what kind of measures the
Islamic system might take to tackle the diplomatic crisis
between Iran and European countries.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the session spelled out a message
that Iran will continue to take tough action on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian diplomats have to be obedient to the order issued
by Iranian Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei, who issued the order on
April 30 to refuse German ambassador to return to Tehran.
</P>
<P>
However, Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani said last
month that Iran wants normal relations with European countries
but the German ambassador has to wait to come back to
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
In April the 64-year-old president attacked Germany for
"destroying 100-year friendship with Iran because of baseless
verdict by the Berlin court" on April 10.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin court ruled that the top political leadership in
Iran was behind the assassination of Kurdish opposition leaders
in Berlin's Mykonos restaurant in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The court gave life imprisonment to one Iranian national
and a Lebanese and sentenced two other Lebanese to long prison
terms on charge of assassinating the four Kurdish dissidents.
</P>
<P>
The verdict sparked diplomatic battle between Iran and
Germany as well as other European countries. EU has recalled
their ambassadors, suspended ministerial level contact and stop
critical dialogue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
