<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Proposal Gaining Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe, which is campaigning for a
lift on the international ban on ivory trade, said today it is
receiving growing support at the ongoing 10th conference of parties
to the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species
(CITES).
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Ambassador to Geneva, Tichaona Jokonya, said a number of
delegations were changing their negative attitude on the proposal to
remove elephants from the list of endangered species.
</P>
<P>
''There is a growing appreciation of Zimbabwe's cause, and the
atmosphere has changed greatly since we started,'' said the Chairman
of the CITES meeting.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, together with Namibia and Botswana, are calling for the
downlisting of the elephant from appendix I, which bans trade in
ivory, to appendix II, which allows controlled trade.
</P>
<P>
The three southern African states argued that their countries could
not sustainably maintain the current large elephant populations while
ivory stockpiles which had accumulated since 1989 could be sold for
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe would need the support of at least two thirds of the 138
CITES members for its proposal, which had been unsuccessful for the
past three meetings, to succeed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
