<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Complains of Refugee Influx </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran, busy with tackling an influx
of refugees from war-torn Afghanistan and northern Iraq, said
today that it will only accept refugees whose lives are in danger.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Husseini, director-general of the Interior Ministry's
Department for Foreign Nationals and Refugees, said that the
ministry has adopted the measures to deal with the refugee influx.
</P>
<P>
"Iran has entered into negotiations with the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and other countries to
help the refugees move to other countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that preliminary negotiations were also held with the
UN officials to establish the UNHCR regional office in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official said that Iran is on top of the list of
countries hosting foreign refugees. About 1.4 million Afghan
refugees, 576,000 Iraqi refugees and migrants from Bangladesh and
Pakistan are living in Iran.
</P>
<P>
While talking with local press, he said, Iran is working to
prepare grounds for repatriation of the refugees to their own
countries.
</P>
<P>
Husseini said after withdrawal of the troops of former
Soviet Union from Afghanistan, 1.38 million Afghan refugees
returned to their country voluntarily, adding that voluntary
return home of 250,000 Afghan refugees this year has stopped
owing to the current crisis in that country.
</P>
<P>
"Due to the fact that the prospect for their return to
Afghanistan is grim, Iran has been proposing that the Afghan
refugees should be accommodated in a third country," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Iraqi refugees living in Iran, he said a program is
prepared to voluntarily repatriate 10,000 Iraqi Kurds to northern
Iraq and since 50 percent of Iraqi refugees are Kurds, their
repatriation would have no problem because Saddam's forces are not
present in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the total assistance of international organizations and
private charity institutes to refugees in Iran was 43 million
U.S. dollars in 1997 which is very slight compared to the costs of
managing over 2 million foreign refugees.
</P>
<P>
According to the Geneva convention on refugees adopted in 1951,
he said, three ways are envisaged concerning the fate of foreign
refugees that are, repatriation, integration into the country
where the refugees are living and settlement of refugees and
migrants in a third country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
