<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Official Proposes Debt-For-Ivory Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries with huge
stockpiles of ivory should consider a debt-for-ivory scheme under
which creditor nations could restructure a country's debt in
exchange for environmental conservation, a policy expert from the
World Wildlife Fund said here today.
</P>
<P>
Director for International Policy of the World Wildlife Fund,
Ginette Hemley, said the debt reduction initiative might be
a practical solution to the ivory stock issue.
</P>
<P>
''It is up to the African countries and the creditor nations
to agree on the debt-for-ivory scheme because it would need to be
on a government-to-government basis,'' said Hemley.
</P>
<P>
The debt-for-ivory scheme was being seen as the most effective
since it would address developing countries's debt burden which
had seen large percentages of national revenue being channelled
to service foreign and domestic debt.
</P>
<P>
When the ban on ivory trade began in 1989, a number of
countries found themselves stuck with stockpiles worth millions
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is lobbying the ongoing Convention on International
Trade in Endangered Species to lift the ban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
