<HEADLINE> Poll Shows: Whites, Blacks Differ on Race Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Black Americans have a far more
pessimistic view of how the races get along than do whites, a new
Gallup survey of race relations finds. But more than half of both
blacks and whites say race relations will always be a problem in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
In general, whites see little to be concerned about when it
comes to opportunities for blacks in jobs, education and housing,
according to the poll released Tuesday. Blacks, however, continue
to see racial discrimination as a factor limiting full equality.
</P>
<P>
Just 34 percent of whites feel the government should make
greater efforts to support minorities, while 59 percent of blacks
see the need for great governmental remedies to inequality.
</P>
<P>
Some measures of white racism seem to show as easing of
discriminatory attitudes such as shrinking white resistance to
interracial marriage, voting for a black for president and sending
their children to school with black classmates.
</P>
<P>
But a majority of both groups believe problems of race are here
with us to stay.
</P>
<P>
Asked if race relations will always be a problem in the United
States, 58 percent of blacks said yes. Among whites, 54 percent
said race relations will always be a problem.
</P>
<P>
The telephone survey of 3,036 adults was conducted January
4-February 28 and had a margin of error of plus or minus 3
percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Animal Body Attacks Zimbabwe on Ivory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A British-based international
organization today accused Zimbabwe, Namibia and Botswana, which
are campaigning for lifting ban on ivory trade, of lacking
political will to solve problems with elephant over-population.
</P>
<P>
International Fund for Animal Welfare (IFAW) leading scientist
Barbara Maas told a press conference here today that other means
could be found to solve problems of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
"Alternative solutions can be found if people have the
political will to look for them. The lack of political will is
the problem here," said Maas who was attending the ongoing
conference of the Convention of International Trade in Endangered
Species (CITES).
</P>
<P>
The three southern African countries had earlier proposed to
the 138-member CITES that the African elephant be downlisted from
Appendix I, which bans trade in ivory, to Appendix II, which
allows for limited and controlled trade.
</P>
<P>
The three countries maintained that the current level of
elephant population was not sustainable, while accumulating ivory
stocks could earn millions of dollars which could be reinvested
in conservation programs.
</P>
<P>
But Maas said there was no scientific proof that elephants
could cause loss of biodiversity as complained by the southern
African countries.
</P>
<P>
She declared that IFAW is opposed to the downlisting of the
elephant because none of the proposing countries had means to
control illegal ivory trade within their borders, while she said
trade in one country could affect the already dwindling elephant
populations in other African countries.
</P>
<P>
The organization was also opposed to the bid by South Africa
to allow trade in parts and derivatives of the white rhino, she
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Drill for Martian Exploratory Journey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian scientists are working
against time to design a drill which will be carried by a Russian
spaceship to Mars in the year 2001, the Egyptian MENA news agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The drill, which will be used to explore the possible existence
of water on the red planet, will be ready in September, said
Muslem Shaltout, the chairman of the Space Research Department at
the National Institute for Astronomical and Geophysical Research.
</P>
<P>
The prototype will be manufactured by the Arab Industrialization
Organization or the Ministry of Military Production, he said.
</P>
<P>
After the prototype is tested, it will be sent to Russia to be
assembled with other equipment on the spaceship.
</P>
<P>
"Marsekhod," the spaceship, will then be launched by a
U.S.-made "Delta" rocket from Cape Canaveral in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The solar-powered Egyptian drill, to be named "Pharoahs' God"
will take samples of earth on Mars at depths of between three and
four meters, according to Shaltout.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. spaceships "Viking 1" and "Viking 2" which were sent
to Mars in 1975 drilled to a depth of only 10 centimeters.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is supplying the drill under an agreement of cooperation
signed among the Egyptian Ministry of Scientific Research, the
Russian Space Research Institute in Moscow and the International
Society for Space Research at Pasadena, U.S., in last September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
