<HEADLINE> EU Should Agree upon Question of Employment: Blair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said in an interview with French television this evening that the
European Union (EU) countries should agree upon the question of
employment during their Amsterdam summit on June 16-17.
</P>
<P>
"What is very important is to agree upon the question of labor
and employment. At the intergovernmental conference, there is an
extraordinary challenge about employment to which we should face
up to," Blair told TF1 television channel.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist government of France has called for a delay of
the signing of the EU monetary Stability Pact, in order to include
clauses on employment and coordination of economic policies into
the pact, which was due to be signed during the Amsterdam summit.
</P>
<P>
The Amsterdam summit is supposed to conclude the negotiations
on the revision of the Maastricht treaty on European economic and
monetary integration.
</P>
<P>
Blair also reiterated his stand that Britain would continue to
run its own border controls and that London will not join the
European single currency until a referendum is held in Britain on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is "very improbable" that Britain will join
the euro "in the first wagon," although London is working in "a
constructive way" with France and Germany on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Blair again expressed his difference with the French Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin over the government regulation of labor
market.
</P>
<P>
"The role of the government today should be to encourage the
flexibility because the world has changed," said Blair.
</P>
<P>
Blair said during the Socialist Congress held in Malmoe,
Sweden, last week that the Socialist parties of Europe today
should seek a third way which is different from both the
conservative parties and the old Socialist governments in seeking
economic growth and social progress.
</P>
<P>
Jospin stressed the importance of social cohesion and the role
for the government to achieve social cohesion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
