<HEADLINE> S.Leone's Envoy to U.N. Warns of Genocide at Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's ambassador to the
United Nations, James Jonah today disclosed a plan of genocide at
his home country, saying even his relatives have been threatened
by the military junta.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in New York this morning, the envoy
said: "Only yesterday, military personnel went to the homes of my
relatives and warned them unless i condemn any Nigerian
intervention, they will be killed."
</P>
<P>
According to the Nigerian Television Authority, Jonah has
asked the Security Council to give "serious consideration" for
setting up a tribunal of the genocide. All the men in
the ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary council in Sierra Leone, including
former rebel Leader Foday Sankoh, are responsible for the planned
genocide, he said.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations have been going on shortly after some soldiers in
Sierra Leone launched a military coup on May 25 which overthrew
the civilian government led by ousted President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The coup, which is wide condemned among the international
community, triggered off the military intervention of the West
African Peacekeeping Force known as ECOMOG in a bid to restore
the civilian government.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the military junta under major Johnny
Paul Koromah are demanding 46 million U.S. Dollars to step down
and allow the return of Kabbah's regime.
</P>
<P>
A delegation sent by Major Koromah to Cote d'Ivoire has ended
its visit and is expected to arrive in Ghana today for talks on
peaceful settlement of the crisis in the west African country.
</P>
