<HEADLINE> UK Industrial Production Rises in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- British industrial production rose
1.2 percent, the highest rate for more than a year and a half in
April, while inflation at the factory gate remained subdued.
</P>
<P>
Prices at the factory gate, a key indicator of inflationary
pressures, rose 0.1 percent in May to show a 1.0 percent change on
May 1996.
</P>
<P>
April's increase pushed the annual rise in industrial output to
2.2 percent, compared with an increase of only 0.2 percent in the
year to March.
</P>
<P>
The rise in domestic demand was helped by an improvement in the
manufacturing sector. Its output grew by 0.6 percent during April,
an annual increase of 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
This was the strongest pace since July 1995, and came as a
surprise following the virtually flat first-quarter figures.
</P>
<P>
There was little sign that export-dominated industries were
suffering more than the rest. However, some of the City economists
said that the government should not be tempted into leaving taxes
alone in the coming budget on July 2.
</P>
<P>
"Just because the weakness of exports is being masked, does not
mean that all is rosy in the economy," one expert said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
