<DOCNO> XIE19970611.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Recommends Extension of UNFICYP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today proposed to extend the mandate of the United Nations
Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFIYP) for a further period of six
months until December 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan said that during
the period of last six months, the number of serious incidents
decreased in Cyprus and both sides of Greek and Turkish Cypriots
generally respected the cease-fire and the status quo.
</P>
<P>
But the tension along the cease-fire lines remained higher than
in the past, he said. There were a number of shooting incidents
and violation of the airspace of Cyprus. Military construction by
both sides continued.
</P>
<P>
There had no changes in the excessive levels of military forces
and armaments in Cyprus and the rate at which they were expanded,
upgraded and modernised, the U.N. chief added while explaining the
reason for the extension of the force.
</P>
<P>
Annan also urged the two sides to make a renewed effort to
reach agreement on measures to reduce tension along the cease-fire
line across the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been partitioned since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed in the north in reaction to a coup in Nicosia by the
military government then ruling Greece. The United Nations has
since been trying to reunite the island on the agreed basis of a
bicommunal federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
